??THE HILLS ARE ALIIIIIIIVE ?? Can you believe this is #Italy?! I used to think that Sicily was the most different part of Italy, but not anymore — #AltoAdige is. This region in the northeast has been passed back and forth between Italy and Austria many times over the centuries, and as a result, it more resembles Austria, Germany, or Switzerland. ? This is one of the 11 things that I learned on my latest trip to Italy — and guess what, that’s a blog post I published today! Click on the link in my profile to find out the other 10. #dolomites #southtyrol ?? Have you been to Alro Adige?

I am home, home, home. ?? Three weeks in #Italy have come to a close. A country I adore; a country I never tire of visiting. I also did a bit of an Instagram experiment — I wanted to see if I could take a good, Instagram-worthy photo of myself every day I was there. And I did (plus this pro photo shoot in #Florence with @alexandrajitariuc). While taking photos of yourself is possibly while traveling solo, it’s a LOT easier and faster when you have friends with you. I enjoyed it. I’ll probably do more of it. ?? I’m so Italy-enamored, I plan to get a post out about it tomorrow on the blog. Stay tuned for that. ???? Did you enjoy the 21 days of photos of me, or do you prefer photos of scenery and stuff?

Say hey to your gargoyle for me. ?? The first two times I went to #Milan, I only stayed for 24 hours and barely saw any of it. This time I had five days to soak it up — but I’ll be honest, as this is the end of a three-week trip, I spent a lot of the time chilling and catching up on work. But I had always wondered about Milan — it’s 1) a big city 2) in Italy 3) with great flight connections. Is this a place where I could live? ?? After enjoying aperitivos and gelato, taking the tram around the city, and trying to genuinely get a sense of what makes Milan tick, I think I COULD live here if necessary — but the burning desire just isn’t there. It’s fun to visit, though, and I’d be happy to add a few days onto the end of a trip next time. But my heart still belongs to Bologna, a city that just radiates warmth and joy. ???? If you had to live somewhere in Italy, where would it be?

Is it true that #Milan is a fashionable town? Um YEP. ?? Last night I went out for aperitivo in a cool part of the city with some local friends and I was blown away by how well everyone was dressed! The men more than the women. Tight fitted suits, perfectly coiffed hair...I felt like such a schlub by comparison! ?? Today I finally saw the top item on my Milan bucket list: The Last Supper. What a painting — it was incredible to see it. The Last Supper sells out months in advance so I went on a tour with @walkstours that included The Last Supper and a tour of Milan’s Duomo, including the rooftop. The last time I saw the Duomo, 15 years ago, it was covered in scaffolding, so this was so much better! Thanks for comping me, @walkstours. ???? Tomorrow is my last full day in #Italy (well, at least until September) — what should I do? Besides eat a ton of gelato?

Train life. ?? Trains are my favorite way to travel #Italy, and while they’re not perfect for EVERYWHERE, they cover a ton of the country. Plus they’re exceedingly pleasant, especially my favorite train, the #Frecciarossa, the high speed train. Huge thanks to @italiarail for comping me two first class Italy rail passes for this trip and allowing me to zip around at 300 kph with ease. You need to book reservations for the high speed trains, but it’s only €10 per train and first class is SOOOOOO nice. The seats are luxurious and they give you free drinks and snacks (including wine — this is Italy after all). I found out yesterday there’s actually a direct Frecciarossa from Torino, in the far northwest, to Lecce, in the far southeast. It takes 11.5 hours and that’s one ride I wouldn’t mind taking! Next time. ?? Have you traveled Italy by train?

This is the best chocolatey beverage you’ve never heard of — the #bicerin! ?? The bicerin — pronounced BEE-chih-REEN — is from the city of #Torino, which I am exploring today. It’s a combination of hot chocolate and coffee topped with a cream floater. It’s delicious — and if you’re starting to feel sleepy, this will give you the rush you need to keep up sightseeing! ? I had mine at Cafe Al Bicerin, which dates back to 1763 and feels like a time capsule. I highly recommend stopping there on a trip to Torino, but I’d love to try other cafes to see if they have a unique twist on it! Torino is a lovely city and it was a super-easy day trip from Milan: just one hour on the high-speed Frecciarossa train. #italy ???? Have you ever had a bicerin? Does it look like something you’d try?

Everything on Instagram is insanely posed, but this is the closest to how I actually look on a normal day. Clutching my camera. No lipstick because I’ll inevitably smear it all over the camera screen and thus all over my face. Fake leather moto jacket on top of whatever dress I *think* will look good, and frankly, I’m rolling the dice. Oh, and let’s not forget the shoes that are completely impractical for climbing a mountain because I thought there were steps to the top! (There are not.) But you know what? These pics are just as real as any of the posed ones. And this was a seriously cool spot (#Mottarrone) — on a clear day you can see seven of Italy’s lakes! I counted five. #piemonte #italia #photographerlife ? What are you getting up to this week?

#ThisIs34. ?? I’m in the closing months of being 34 years old, and enjoying every minute of it. I have yet to reach an age that I am genuinely uncomfortable to be, and even though turning 35 in August will@push me into a new age bracket, I’m embracing it. Aging is a privilege. There are always new and exciting adventures ahead. ? I’ve had the most beautiful two days in Lake Orta — I need to come back here someday! ?? How old are you now and how do you feel?

Everyone is familiar with Lake Como, but there are even better lakes in this part of #Italy — like #LakeMaggiore in #Piedmont. This immense lake is pure glamour. I only wish I had come a few months ago when the mountains were capped with snow! So beautiful. If you’re coming here, I recommend checking out the small town of #Stresa and taking the ferry to the islands. Stresa has some good restaurants and Wes Anderson-looking hotels. It’s definitely not as busy or as famous here as Lake Como. And if you stick around, there are even quieter lakes to explore — like Lake Orta, where I just arrived for the next two days. ?? #piemonte #lagodimaggiore ???? Do you have a special lake you’ve discovered on your travels?

Confession time — ever used #Tinder on your travels? I have. Not often, but enough to make things interesting. ?? If you’re traveling solo, meeting someone via Tinder can be a great way to gain insight into the culture. ?? And once when I was in Guatemala with one of my tours, my girls and I used Tinder to invite as many guys as possible to meet up with us at a bar. ?? But MOST interesting is when you go to a conference full of your friends and colleagues whom you adore but see rarely, and use Tinder just to see who’s single and looking at the moment. ?? Thinking of using it? Go for it. Just make sure that someone you trust knows your plans and check in with him or her. ? Have you used Tinder or other dating apps on your travels?

The #Dolomites really do deliver. ? For my final day at @ciasasalares in #SouthTyrol, I went on a hike into the mountains! HOW GORGEOUS IS THIS?! We literally started on the ground by the hotel and climbed on and on and on. ??????? I held up surprisingly well — last time I hiked at altitude, in Vail, I was exhausted at the mildest exertions. This was just fun — and stunning. When you walk to the top, you have a 360-degree view of jagged peaks. I felt like Maria in The Sound of Music! ?? Some wine and cacio e pepe later and a dip in the hot tub were DEFINITELY earned! ? Thanks to the Ciasa Salares staff for making it such a beautiful stay. Today @cailinoneil and I are on a 8.5-hour journey by van, bus, and four trains to Lake Como. So excited to see the scenery tomorrow! #altoadige #italy #italia ???? Where is your favorite place to hike?

Find someone who looks at you the way I look at cured meats. ?? Last night @cailinoneil and I had the ultimate dining experience here at @ciasasalares in the Dolomites — wine tasting in the gorgeous cellar, with strange and wonderful wines from Calabria, Venezia Giulia, Emilia, and more. We finished with fondue — both meat and cheese! And then a visit to the CHOCOLATE ROOM, which is exactly what it sounds like (see my Stories for me singing the Willy Wonka song). Honestly, the speck here in Alto Adige is far and beyond the usual prosciutto — I cant get enough of it. It’s feathery and smoky. And the wines are GORGEOUS. This culinary mountain retreat has been exactly what we needed. Truthfully, we both arrived here sick as a dog after too much conference, but after two days here we are nearly recovered. Fun fact: one of the wines was called “Insolente,” which is Italian for dickhead!?? What’s your favorite wine?

The #Dolomites are MAGICAL. ? Today I went on a tour of the region with @ciasasalares and I enjoyed the gorgeous peaks, wood cabins, and chocolate box-like villages. This region delivers on every front — and my friends in Emilia-Romagna night kill me for saying this, but the local form of prosciutto here, speck, is TRANSCENDENTLY GOOD. I nearly died. ? Tomorrow is all about the hiking. Check out some more videos from the Dolomites on my Stories! ???? What are you up to this fine Tuesday?

Hello #Dolomites! ?? After the insanity of #Traverse19, I knew I would need to relax and recover — so @cailinoneil and I headed to @ciasasalares. This is the view from our sweet balcony! This resort is gorgeous and looks far more like something in Austria or Germany than in #Italy! It’s not a surprise — this Italian region, #SouthTyrol or #AltoAdige, has a long history of being passed back and forth between the two countries, and both German and Italian are spoken here, as well as the local language Ladin. Over the next few days we will be exploring the gorgeous mountain landscapes, eating delicious food, and soaking up the spa. Just what we need after four days of parties, networking, and too little sleep. I can’t wait! ?? This top is by @dereklam (man do I love that brand) and the sunglasses are @tomford as always. ? Have you been to the Dolomites?

What are your feelings on...gelato? ?? When I first went to #Italy during my semester abroad in 2004, I got into the habit of having gelato every day. I still do almost every day when I’m back. It’s so much better than regular ice cream — and it’s cheap and served in small portions! ? Here are some tips: look for a gelateria with metal tins, the gelato isn’t piled up super high, the banana is gray, and the pistachio is brownish. If you follow that advice, you’ve probably found a decent gelato place. Here in #Trento I loved the gelato at a place called Gelateria Cherry. ?? My favorite flavors? I love the combo of limone and lampone (lemon and raspberry), but I’m always up for stracciatella (chocolate chip) or fragola (strawberry). #visittrentino #Traverse19 What’s your favorite gelato flavor?

Romance on #LakeGarda. ?? My little excursion to the town of #RivaDelGarda yesterday was one of the highlights of my time in #Trentino and all of #Italy! The lake is SO impressive — wild, windy, and surrounded by enormous mountains. It simultaneously feels like the Alps and the tropics — such a cool place! I had barely heard of Lake Garda before this trip, even having traveled extensively in Italy, but now it’s one of my favorite nature destinations in the country. Trentino, you are a superstar. I can’t believe how much you have to offer. #Traverse19 ??? What destination surprised you?

#Trentino, you are SO pretty — even when you make my hair crazy! ?? Today my friends and I road tripped down to #LakeGarda! This enormous lake is surrounded by tall mountains, while palm trees dot the landscape — it’s an interesting mix! ??? We visited the town of #RivaDelGarda, which is pastel-perfect. It reminded me a lot of Liguria, even though we are far from the sea! We climbed 165 steps to the top of the tower and the view was outstanding. I wish I had more time to explore Lake Garda, and I’m curious to see how it compares to Lake Como and Lake Maggiore later in the trip. #visittrentino #Traverse19 ?? Have you been to Lake Garda? Or anywhere that has both mountains and palm trees?

Greetings from #Trentino, #Italy! How gorgeous are these mountains?! ?? I’m here in the city of #Trento (as in Trent, as in yes, the Council of Trent — remember that?) for the #Traverse19 conference, where I’ll be speaking about the most important things I’ve learned in my nine-year professional travel blogging career. Today we took the cable car to the top of the mountain and enjoyed this splendid view! ? So far, Trento feels cozy, unpretentious and low-key. The perfect spot to sit at an outdoor table with friends drinking cassis spritzes! ?? I’m so looking forward to what the next few days bring. Tomorrow I am exploring Trento and hope to get to Lake Garda. You can follow along in real time on my Stories! ? And hell yes, I’m rocking the @voodoovixenldn overalls from @uniquevintage. I LOVE THESE SO DAMN MUCH. #visittrentino ?? What are you getting up to this weekend?

Every time I go to #Italy, without failure, I start dreaming of owning a #Vespa. ?? How amazing would it be to cruise the streets of Manhattan on one of these? Well, let’s be honest. New York is too gross for Vespa riding...and part of me dreams of moving to Italy again. I love the lifestyle here and the cost of living is SO much lower. I mean, good bottles of wine for €4? Aperitivo buffets with a fancy cocktail for under €15? Pizza for €5? ?? Maybe I’ll make the move someday, to well-connected Milan or my beloved Bologna. Until then, I’ll visit as often as I can. ?? Yesterday I booked a photo shoot in #Florence to commemorate 15 years since my semester abroad. The lovely @alexandrajitariuc took portraits of me all over the trendy Santo Spirito neighborhood. I am VERY happy with them — not least because I look a million times better at 34 than I did at 20! Never forget what a cruel time the early 2000s were to fashion. ???? Where do you dream of moving someday?

Greetings from #Florence, #Italy! ?? What a trip it is to be back here -- I studied abroad here 15 years ago in 2004! This is my first trip back since 2006, and WOW, is it a different place. It’s got golf carts and WiFi and an Apple store. ? Honestly, don’t come here in the high season at all (which it is now) — it’s just WAY too crowded and dominated by tourists. You can barely move in the city center. It makes me feel lucky for experiencing Florence as a 20-year-old because I didn’t know any better — I just thought it was amazing. And to be fair, the artistic treasures here are sublime — it’s just that Florence is a little too small to contain all these tourists. I’m glad I came back to see it, but I don’t think I’ll be back unless I have a VERY good reason. Today my heart belongs to cities like Bologna where you can just chill among the locals and get spoken to in Italian first, not English. ?? I have to admit I spent most of today tracking down my old haunts — some of the awful Irish pubs I frequented still exist, like JJ’s and The Old Stove. And I had to have pizza at the restaurant across from my old apartment, Le Collinine, now called Oinos. See more on my Stories today. ?? Did you study abroad? Did you ever go back?

Did you know that #Bologna is the best food city in #Italy? Even Italians in other cities grudgingly concede that Bologna and the surrounding #EmiliaRomagna region do food better than anywhere else. ?? Today I went to my favorite Bologna restaurant, Osteria dell’Orsa, with my friend @domestiphobia, and had my favorite dish, tagliatelle ragú. This is the REAL dish spaghetti bolognese is based on, only a million times better. And at this cheap and cheerful place, it costs a lovely €6.50. Go early to get a spot! ?? Emilia-Romagna is also the home of prosciutto di Parma, parmigiano reggiano, traditional balsamic vinegar from Modena, and all kinds of delicious produce, from truffles to chestnuts to heirloom tomatoes. And don’t forget to wash it all down with cold sparkling lambrusco! ??Come here hungry! #InEmiliaRomagna #Blogville ???? What’s your favorite food region around the world?

What happens when a city you love — BOLOGNA, ITALY — changes? ?? #Bologna has been my favorite city in Italy for a long time — I love the vibe, the food, the culture. And while I’ve spent a ton of time here, I haven’t been back since 2013. Today when out for a walk, I was sad to see my favorite aperitivo bar and tiramisu spot were gone. And it felt surprising to see ramen, bibimbap and poke spots! And there are a ton of tour groups now, but considering how much work I’ve been doing for Emilia-Romagna tourism since 2011, more tour groups just means I’ve done my job! ???? Colson Whitehead once said that you become a New Yorker when the New York you love starts disappearing amidst the new developments. It’s just a testament to how much you love the city. And Bologna is freaking amazing!!! I’m so happy to be here amongst the sunshine, the red walls, the 11 AM Lambrusco breaks, and the squacquerone cheese. See my Stories for much more of Bologna. #inEmiliaRomagna ? Have you ever returned to a place that changed?

For the first year after I moved to New York in 2016, I would cry every time I took an Uber to the airport. After years of traveling the world, I had finally chosen a place just for me. I loved my stationary life and didn’t want to leave it, even for somewhere awesome. I got over it, but sometimes I get a bit teary as I drive over Randall’s Island and watch the skyline go by. ? I won’t be crying when I fly out tonight. In part because I’m taking the subway (because there’s no way in hell I’m taking an Uber to JFK during rush hour on a Friday night, aka paying to be even more miserable). On to Italy. It’s going to be amazing. ??: @marijanamarinovic_mariachi

Have you ever been to the #Highline before? This elevated park in New York is a gorgeous place to take a walk! You stroll above the city and enjoy the greenery. And I kind of love gazing into the windows of the apartments that overlook it, wondering about the people who live there. Kind of weird to have your bed in plain view of so many people!! ?? The HighLine is debuting a new section on June 5 called the Spur, right by Hudson Yards. I got to preview it yesterday. It includes a gorgeous sculpture by Simone Leigh called Brick House: a sixteen-foot-tall bust of a black woman with cowrie shell-adorned braids. This new section is totally worth a visit — come check it out from June 5 onwards! And head to Mercado Little Spain afterward for some jamon y queso. #HighlineSpur @highlinenyc ? I’m LOVING my new cropped fitted @voodoovixenldn overalls, which I got from @uniquevintage. SO DAMN CUTE. Got the striped top there too. ?? Have you been to the HighLine? What did you think?

FASHION. ?????? I loved this @dereklam dress so much that this weekend I hired photographer @marijanamarinovic_mariachi to do a photo shoot in #Soho! So glad to have some nice #NYC photos in my portfolio. ?? In the past year I’ve really upped my fashion game. It makes a big difference in my photos and it just makes me so much happier! Thank you for capturing this, Marijana! ? Do watch my Stories today — I have a new fashion show with the dresses I’m debating bringing to Italy. Go cast your vote! #yellowdress #newyorklife What are you excited about right now?

I used to think I was a beach person. Nope. I’m actually a mountains person. ? Beaches are nice and all, but nothing makes me as happy as seeing mountains spring up in all directions around me. This photo was taken in #Vail, #Colorado, in 2017 — I absolutely loved the summer hiking there!! A few of my other favorite mountain destinations are the city of Innsbruck, Austria (where you are surrounded by mountains and you can take a funicular to the top for hiking), the White Mountains in New Hampshire (where I spent my summers camping growing up), and, believe it or not, Antarctica, which is covered with gorgeous mountains. This summer, I’m visiting the Dolomites for the first time and I can’t wait. ?? What about you? What’s your favorite mountain destination?

Kicking off summer in #Bushwick. ?? I have two more days with this fabulous yellow dress by @dereklam I rented for the month — so I booked a pro photo shoot wearing it in SoHo yesterday! Can’t wait to see the results, which I should get in a few days. For now, here’s the after-shoot activity — hanging at @brooklynbeergarden with @katrinkasasha on her annual visit from Istanbul. It’s a cool outdoor beer garden that serves exclusively Brooklyn beer and wine. I had no idea I’d find a mural that matched my dress! ? What are you up to this fine Sunday?

So, where are you spending Memorial Day weekend? I’m here in New York. ??? No desire to go away when I have Italy coming up in a week. Plus, New York is actually pretty nice on holiday weekends — as long as you stick to places where tourists don’t go. It’s calmer, airier, more peaceful. And even as I type this out in busy SoHo (this pic is from Battery Park City a year ago), I’m eager to get back to m fun neighborhood bars in my untouristy corner of Harlem. ? Where are you spending the weekend?

I am in hardcore ITALY planning mode! ???? A week from today I fly to Milan and commence a 3-week journey through one of my favorite countries on the planet. I’ll be visiting Trentino to speak at the @traverseevents conference — a new region! I’ll be visiting new areas like the Dolomites, Lake Como, Torino, and Verona, and returning to Bologna and Milan. ?? Even though I have a goal of visiting 100+ countries (and am currently at 79), I will continue visiting Italy again and again. It is THAT good. The fashion. The beauty. The food and the wine. The immaculately groomed men who spend a little too much time on their appearance. ?? I can’t wait. This trip is going to be amazing. ?? Have you been to #Italy? Have any tips for me?

WHAT THE HELL IS GOING ON?! ?? The other night a K train arrived at Canal St. on the C platform. THE K TRAIN DOES NOT EXIST. So I quickly grabbed a selfie with it (I mean, my name is Kate, I had to!) before it rolled away. ?? Then I got on Wikipedia. There USED to be a K train — but it was discontinued in December 1988. Trains used to have single letters if they were local and double if they were express, but they later scraped that system. Most strangely, today’s C trains still contain those signs predating 1988, and they are inside the trains of today. Some pranksters got a hex key and turned it until it brought up the K signs. Isn’t that insane? These trains still contain signs FROM WHEN REAGAN WAS PRESIDENT. How? How?!?! THIS IS SOME HOT TUB TIME MACHINE BULLSHIT!!! ?? Also, I posted this to the NYC subreddit and it became my top post ever. Yay! But if anything, it once again highlights how disastrous @nygovcuomo has been for the subway. Stop giving our subway money away to upstaters, dude. This was a funny moment but our subway is in a state of emergency and it’s only going to get worse.? Have you ever seen a glitch in the matrix in real life?

Sometimes a sunset can be a REALLY pink sunset. ??????This is the view from #ShirleyHeights in #Antigua. Here’s a sunset photography tip I got from @speakeasytravel on a trip to Tuscany back in 2013: turn the white balance onto “shade” and see what happens. If it’s a blue sunset, it will warm it up nicely; if it’s looking pink, it will turn REALLY pink. It was a cloudy night at Shirley Heights, not the bright blue seascape I had hoped for, but playing with the white balance gave me some awesome sunset pictures. Definitely the most photogenic spot on the island! #loveantiguabarbuda #whatcoollookslike Do you ever tweak your sunset photos, or so you like to keep them natural?

Weird question — do you guys remember “Sharon, Lois and Bram”? It was a kids’ show in the early 90s. It was on Nickelodeon. The three adults would sing and play guitar and do sketches for kids. And Lois almost always wore off-the-shoulder dresses with a ruffly panel hanging over the bust — exactly like this one. So when these dresses came back into style, I laughed — these are Lois dresses! I never thought I would be sampling Lois’s wardrobe at the age of 34. Just hand me a tambourine! I guess everything comes back eventually. ?? This dress is a rental from Rent the Runway by @amandauprichard. I fucking LOVED IT, even though it had to be pinned to within an inch of its life. ?? And I wore it on our catamaran cruise from St. John’s in #Antigua. SUCH a fun night, my favorite activity in Antigua. When you’re heading out on a boat, you want a dress that looks gorgeous in a breeze! #LoveAntiguaBarbuda #whatcoollookslike ?? Do you remember that show or am I seriously showing my age here??

I should totally try to sell this pineapple pic from #Antigua. I swear I’ve seen tons like it at West Elm. ?? Antigua has the sweetest, most delicious pineapples in the world — but my favorite pineapple tip actually comes from a trip to Louisiana a few years ago. Wealthy families would welcome you with a pineapple upon arrival — after all, it’s a symbol of welcome. But if you received a pineapple on your breakfast tray the next morning, the message was a discreet YOU BEST BE LEAVING. ?? Subtle and vicious. #?? #loveantiguabarbuda #whatcoollookslike ?? Would you hang a print of this photo on your wall?

Champagne, plunge pool, sittin’ in a birdcage. ?? While staying at the @verandahresort in #Antigua, I got to do a visit next door to the new property @eliteisland resorts is building: Hammock Cove. Five stars, adults only, each suite has its own plunge pool. SWANK AS HELLLLL. A modern and gorgeous all-inclusive.  It’s opening this December and I kind of really want to go back when it opens. My secret boyfriend @therock and I would have a lovely time here. ?? #loveantiguabarbuda #whatcoollookslike Who would you take with you to a resort with your own private plunge pool? Tag them here!

Home safe from #Antigua and I miss it so much already! ?? I miss my little cottage at @verandahresort, I miss sitting in the water hammock sun the sunshine, I miss putting on a fabulous dress and posing on the island’s gorgeous backdrops, and most of all, I miss my friends. Thank you to @traverseevents and @antiguaandbarbuda for putting on an amazing week of programming and showing us your shining star of a country. It was one of the best times I’ve had in a long time. Can’t wait to get to writing about it. ?? So what’s next? In 17 days I fly off to Italy for three weeks, including Traverse in Trentino! ?? This bikini and high slit pants combo is by @trinaturk — I listed after it for a year and finally bought it all (on sale!) right before the trip. ?? Thank you @cailinoneil for this photo! #LoveAntiguaBarbuda #whatcoollookslike ?? What are you getting up to this summer?

It’s time to leave #Antigua. I’m bereft. ?? This was one of the best trips of my life — a trip filled with moments of creativity and friendship and life affirmation. I need to carry this happiness within me a little longer. ?? We finished our trip with a gorgeous cruise on a catamaran. It had been cloudy all day but it melted off into beautiful blue sky and a killer sunset. #LoveAntiguaBarbuda #whatcoollookslike

This trip to #Antigua has been incredible. Being here enjoying the beaches and breezes, surrounded by 40 of my friends, and having constant creative conversations — it’s like a balm for my soul. ?? I’ve been in a bit of a funk lately — more of a general malaise than anything else. I’ve been spinning my wheels in lots of ways. This trip picked me up again and made me feel like my heart grew ten sizes. I’m coming back to New York a better person. Thank you to this little island for getting me there. #LoveAntiguaBarbuda #whatcoollookslike ? Has a trip ever made you realize you had been sad for a long time?

Do you like views? #Antigua has lots of views like this. ?? I’m so glad I’ve been spending time actually exploring the island instead of just hanging out on the beach. Well, the beach part is nice, too. ?? You can rent a car on your own or go on a tour, like our open-door safari. Just be careful on the roads! Caribbean driving is pretty wild. This is my favorite view that we had. #LoveAntiguaBarbuda #whatcoollookslike ?? Where do you wish you were right now?

Look at my pretty little friend! ?????? Today in #Antigua I headed to its capital and largest city, St. John’s. Saturday is market day and you’ll find tons of vendors selling produce. Most Caribbean cities aren’t on visitors’ itineraries, but I like walking around, seeing what vegetables are in season, and hanging out with people just living their lives. This is something I always make sure to do on each trip. BUT LOOK I FOUND A CUTE TINY PINEAPPLE!!! It smelled SO sweet! Is it safe for a woman to travel alone in Central America? HELL YES. ?? Many people assume that Central America is too dangerous for a woman to travel alone — after all, if all those migrants are fleeing violence and poverty, how good can it be? Well, that doesn’t tell the whole story. ?? Central America is full of gorgeous rainforests and volcanoes and beaches. The people are SO warm and welcoming. There is a well-established backpacker trail and whether you want to meet new people or keep to yourself, you’ll be able to do that in Central America. Some of my favorite spots are Little Corn Island in Nicaragua, Lake Atitlán in Guatemala, and Caye Caulker in Belize. ?? Today’s post is a long, in-depth guide to solo female travel in Central America. If you have a friend who is thinking of traveling there, send her this post! The link is in my profile. ? Have you been to Central America? What was your favorite place?

It’s springtime in #NYC, and you know what that means — FERRY SEASON! ?? Once again, I’m back on the #StatenIslandFerry, one of my favorite things to do in New York and one place where I always take visitors (including my bud @anubhamomin yesterday!). What makes it so great? The views are outstanding, it’s so nice to feel the wind in your face, it’s the perfect duration (30 minutes), you go right past the Statue of Liberty, and oh yes, IT’S FREE. In the words of @petedavidson, “If Staten Island is so great, why is it free to get there?” ?? You can do this 24 hours a day year-round, but it’s much nicer when the weather is beautiful. I usually just turn around and come right back, but sometimes I like to visit the @flagshipbrewery, a 10-minute walk from the ferry terminal. You should do it! ?? Welcome to my new habit. ?? I’ve been reading a lot about habits lately — James Clear’s “Atomic Habits” is an excellent book! (Thanks for the rec, @legalnomads.) It gets into the science of habit formation. One of the sections is about stacking habits (when you do one thing, you automatically do another thing) and arranging them so your reward comes last. This is what I do: after I go to the gym (@equinox West 92nd), which I do five to six times per week, I walk over to Central Park and walk around the reservoir, then I go to @birchcoffee on 96th and Columbus and reward myself with an americano. That walk, gym to coffee shop, takes about one hour, earns me 6,000 steps, and burns about 330 calories. The perfect complement to lifting weights or Zumba or whatever class I’m trying out at the moment. As a bonus, that Birch is located right between Trader Joe’s and Whole Foods so I can do my grocery shopping after! ?? Have you ever tried to form better habits? How did it work out for you?

Public transit isn’t great in this part of the country, so doing a road trip would let me be able to see a ton of the landscape. Definitely a good choice for spring or fall. ?? One of the most popular questions I get is “How did you become a successful travel blogger?” A tough question, because it was due to a few dozen smart decisions I made from childhood up until the present. I finally decided to write it — an autobiography of sorts. I became a successful blogger because I had already been blogging on a near/daily basis for the past seven years before I decided to get serious and start a more professional travel blog. I had already developed my writing voice, and I had spent years building websites and traveling already. When you look back in time, it’s like I was always getting ready for this career — it’s just that I had no idea I was doing it! ?? The post is long but VERY entertaining — one of my favorites I’ve ever written. The link is in my profile. I hope you enjoy it! ? What seemingly innocent decision got you to where you are today?

In the past few years, I’ve gotten to a much better position with accepting my body for what it is. With that, though, I’ve realized that the safari outfit I bought for Kenya in October was super tight in #Guyana in March, especially the pants. ?? My eating habits haven’t been great over the past few months, and even though I work out a ton, it wasn’t enough to make up for what I was eating. So it’s time for another round of #Whole30! ??30 days of clean eating: no grains, dairy, legumes, sugar, alcohol, or anything artificial or processed. It’s simpler than it sounds — you basically eat meat, fish, or eggs with veggies for every meal. I did it in 2017 and LOVED how it made me feel — I had tons of energy, didn’t have so much as a headache, and my period was pain-free (!!). ?? I highly recommend trying it if you have a 30-day time period with no travel or eating obligations. You might find out your body is sensitive to something you didn’t know about. ?? I just did a body composition scan at the gym to compare before and after and found out that yeah, I’ve packed on some fat this winter, but I also have more muscle on my body than ever before! That makes me happy! ???? Here’s hoping that a month of cutting out junk food not only lets me fit into my pants again, but helps me lift heavier weights, dance harder at Zumba, throw my friends’ kids in the air without getting winded, hike harder through the Dolomites in June, and get into some healthier cooking habits that last long-term. Because it’s all about feeling great — not looking good. ?? Have you ever tried Whole 30 or any kind of food reset?

Ah, a beautiful view of the rice paddies of Bali. NOPE, I LIED — it’s #Guyana! This is an area of the #Rupununi region near Karanambu Lodge. Guyana is a great spot for bird-watching. Birds aren’t usually my thing — but it’s hard not to be entranced at a place like this! Storks we’re flying around everywhere at sunset, illuminated by the bright sunshine. ?? When you saw this photo, where did you think it was from?

Is this not the CUTEST little #otter you’ve ever seen?! ?? “Little” is a bit of a misnomer — this is actually a six-month-old GIANT OTTER living at Karanambu Lodge in the North Rupununi region of #Guyana. They have been protecting these beautiful creatures since the 1980s. I got to see two of the little guys play and chomp on some fish heads. It’s amazing that they follow you down to the river like puppies! Later I went on a hike and got to see a family of otters playing in the river. Karanambu is a magical place and I’m so glad I got to see these animals in real life. ?? Did you know that otters have a pocket in their fur for their favorite rock?

Ever heard of #KaieteurFalls? Most people haven’t, but you should have — they’re the highest single-drop waterfalls in the world. But because they’re in #Guyana, few people have even heard of them. ???? The falls are little developed — if you want to see them, you need to visit on a day trip by plane either from Georgetown or en route from Lethem. (There is also a five-day overland camping trip if you dare.) We really lucked out and got to do a scenic flight with views of Roraima and some other cool waterfalls. Once you get to the falls, there’s nothing there — just a small building with a bathroom and a shop. There are four different viewing areas — this one, Johnson’s View, is the furthest back and offers the most panoramic view. The falls are often more lush than this, especially in rainy season — but trust me, you ONLY want to visit Guyana in the dry season. ?? What’s your favorite #waterfall?

I’M BACK!! Guys...my adventure in the remote interior of #Guyana was EVEN BETTER than I thought it would be. OH MY GOD.
????
Imagine the most beautiful, untouched scenery for hundreds of miles. I saw an anteater, giant otters, and watched a team capture a caiman lizard the size of a crocodile. I rode an ATV over termite mounds into the sunset. I swam in a creek and hung from a palm tree like a monkey. I hiked a mountain and scooted down on sizzling hot rocks. I photographed cowboys roping and branding cattle. I watched Roraima (!!) rise defiantly above the clouds. I stayed with welcoming indigenous families who celebrate Holi and listen to Hindi music. I lived happily with little electricity and no internet, and I developed a fine crust of sweat and dirt on my body that would re-emerge moments after washing. I stood before Kaieteur Falls in wonder. And it wasn’t all good — at one point I saw a mouse kick its droppings off the ceiling and onto me; at another time, a cockroach hatched its babies underneath my jeans. Why do I share this? Because Guyana is a HELL of an adventure — but most people can’t handle the rougher aspects.
????
If you’re one of the few who can, this is one of the most rewarding adventure destinations you can visit — a place so new to tourism that lodges exist on word of mouth. There are few places in this world that are full of incredible attractions, safe to visit, and have almost no tourists. This is one of them.
????
Much more on Guyana soon. I can’t wait to write about it! ??: @ohlivitup

Is it safe for a women to travel alone in #SouthAfrica? Yes — BUT only for experienced solo travelers who do their research and preparation. ?? I LOVE South Africa. I love it fiercely. It’s one of the most beautiful countries on the planet. It has the best wine in the WORLD (just my opinion ??). But South Africa has a high crime rate and you have to guard against that constantly. You can’t just go hang out on an empty beach like you would in Thailand; you can’t drive through a city you’re unfamiliar with at night like you would do in the United States. Want to travel South Africa? YOU SHOULD — but you need to do the proper research first. ?? FINALLY, today I post something I’ve wanted to write for years: my solo female travel guide to #Paris. ?? I LOVE Paris, I’ve been well over a dozen times, and I’ve spent a lot of time there solo. But Paris is actually a lot rougher than people think it’s going to be. There’s a lot of crime, the street harassment is awful, the pickpocketing is insidious, and perhaps no other city in the world targets tourists for scams worse than Paris. Does that mean you shouldn’t go? No! It means you should do your research so you know how to avoid the worst of it. ?? My post is chock full of useful information for traveling solo in Paris. The link is in my profile. I hope you enjoy it and share it with someone who wants to go to Paris! #pariscartepostale ?? Have you been to Paris? Share your best Paris travel tip below!

Do you ever think about clothes in terms of “cost per wear”? Take the amount an item costs and divide it by the number of times you wear it. By that measure, it’s okay to spend more on something you use all the time, like an expensive everyday purse or leather jacket (maybe $2 per wear), and absurd to splash out on a gown you’ll only wear once (say $250 per wear). These days I rent most of my trendy pieces, but this is a dress I bought that I’m going to wear FOREVER — it’s simple, it’s a bright color, it’s flattering, it’s got a cool neckline, and it looks good everywhere from Puerto Rico to Italy. (Now the bad news: I bought this years ago from ModCloth and don’t shop there anymore because they were bought by Wal-Mart.) I love you, burgundy dress! ??: @dangerousbiz ?? Have you ever thought about your clothing as in cost per wear?

Oh man. The first time I posted this photo, back in 2015, it was a disaster. One of my Indian readers commented, “Dear Kate, I’ve noticed you’ve gained a lot of weight. Is it hard to stay in shape while traveling?” ??????? That hurt a lot, even coming from someone from a country where it’s not as taboo to comment on someone’s body. Especially since I knew I had gained weight but thought I looked better than usual in this photo and decided to post it anyway. What a mistake. (The commenter was reamed out by my readers, and she then she messaged me to say not to worry, she unfollowed me on all my social media just to be on the safe side. Insult to injury!!) ? It has taken a LONG time to get myself to a place of body acceptance, which I think is much more important than hitting an arbitrary body goal. How did that happen? No idea. I just don’t worry about that stuff the way I used to. I used to be obsessed with getting my nose done someday; today I don’t even think about it. And you know what helped a lot? Finding fitness that I actually love. The other day I deadlifted more weight than I ever have — and did 5 sets of 5 reps with it. ??????? I felt like such a badass! Weightlifting and Zumba both give me a lot of joy. Today evaluating my body is all about seeing what cool stuff it can do. And it can do a LOT of cool things. ?? Have you found more body acceptance in time?

Let’s talk about street harassment. It sucks. ?? Here I am in #León, #Nicaragua, in 2015. I adored Nicaragua and Léon, except for one thing — the street harassment was THE WORST. Probably the worst of any country I’ve visited (and the fact that I love Nicaragua so much tells you just how good of a country it is). Everywhere I went, men would yell stuff at me, and when you’re traveling solo, that doesn’t make you feel safe. So I adapted. I wore jeans everywhere, even when it was SO hot and miserable, because that’s how Nicaraguan women dress and I would get fewer catcalls. I also chose a guesthouse with a restaurant in it because I would get men yelling at me the moment I stepped outside at night. (Day was far better.) And at night I would get cabs for ridiculously short distances just to avoid the men. Street harassment rarely escalated beyond yelling, though, and it’s just something you have to deal with. I’m glad I haven’t let it stop me from actually traveling. ? How do you deal with street harassment while traveling?

According to them, flights are the most inexpensive in the fall -- and I highly recommend visiting Paris in October for great weather and smaller crowds! Check out @KAYAK’s Travel Hacker Guide for more. It has tons of awesome travel ideas! The link is in my profile. ?? This post is in partnership with @KAYAK. ? Where do you want to go in 2019?

The truth? Grocery shopping in #NYC is the WORST. Tiny aisles, huge crowds, and without having a car to load up, you can only take as much as you can carry. Sometimes I do Instagram Stories of the lines at Trader Joe’s because you guys will freak out at how they snake around the store! And did you know that because New York is a paradox, often Whole Foods is the cheapest option for basics like beans and pasta?! Well, yesterday I finished my Zumba class and needed a block of parmigiano reggiano so I dropped into one of the tiny grocery stores that I usually avoid for $$$ reasons...and I was spellbound. The produce was stacked PERFECTLY. It was so satisfying to my brain! I guess they restock on Sunday mornings. ?? What have you been cooking lately? I’ve been making a ton of Instant Pot risotto. Last night was asparagus.

I am KICKING MYSELF for not getting this photo up yesterday!! I’ve been saving it for months!!! ??But who cares? February 15 is the REAL holiday. The day when candy is on sale. The day when restaurants are bearable. The day when you don’t get whacked in the eye with bouquets on the subway. Which is why I’m actually celebrating today (though yesterday I did wear a pink tank top to the gym —festive!). ??This pic is from a Qatar Airways gala I attended in November. They actually had a WALL OF ROSES Kim and Kanye’s wedding-style. So cool! And did you know that ?? is the most popular emoji in the Middle East? Such a nice way to show love! These roses were JUICY — huge and red and thick and soft.?? Hope you enjoy your candy today!

Instagram followers, WHERE DID YOU GO, MAN?! ?? In case you missed it, there was a massive Instagram purge last night. LOTS of accounts were deleted. I’m now followed by a lot less, which sucks, because I’m going to have to update my 2019 media kit again. ?? But let there be a lesson in all this — you can’t just be an Instagrammer. You need to have a digital home for you work that is your own, not some other company’s. This can all vanish in the blink of an eye. You are the product. ? My dear friends, it’s too late not to have a website of your own. Plan on getting one ASAP. ?? How did the purge hit you?

If I say it's the best concert of my life, you KNOW it's something special -- and I got to experience it thanks to @Chase. #ad ? This December I went to Dallas to see a legendary performer -- a certain British singer-songwriter with a penchant for sparkly suits and outlandish sunglasses. You know the one. If you have the Chase British Airways Visa, you have access to special events like this one: not only tickets to the concert, but access to a PRIVATE BOX with all-you-can-drink cocktails and a ton of food. And that's not all -- before the concert, we got to attend a special reception at the Reunion Tower with live music and drinks. ?? It made for such a special weekend in Dallas, and I wrote about it on my blog today. Link in profile. Hope you enjoy it! ??

If I could live anywhere else in the world, where would it be? ? My answer used to be wild and romantic — I could move to Buenos Aires and learn to tango and hit up the milongas every week, pressed up against some rando with whom there would be no funny business, as it was all for the love of the dance. Or I could live in Granada, Spain! Watching those purple sunsets over the Alhambra as flamenco notes gently played all around me. Ha. Honestly, I would have gone crazy in either city. ?? These days I’m more practical. I’m still in my “NEW YORK OR NOWHERE” phase, and right now it feels like it’s going to last forever, but who knows? Maybe I’ll tire of it. If I wanted to live elsewhere, I would get the German artist visa (basically a freelancer visa) and move to Berlin. And if I somehow had the privilege to live elsewhere in the EU, I’d live in Paris or Amsterdam or London (Brexit pending, etc), or maybe Stockholm or Copenhagen. Romance may have won me over in the past. But today I need a city where I can live without a car, a city with a well-connected airport, a city with diversity, a city with interesting art, and a city that I could never come close to exploring fully. I love the feeling of being lost and home simultaneously. ??: @jiyangc in Paris. ?? If you could live anywhere else, where would you go?

Ah, what a beautiful Mediterranean village. OKAY, I LIED. It’s #Wales! Specifically the village of #Tenby in #Pembrokeshire. ?????????????? I spent a few years living in the UK. Kind of accidentally, and never officially (I kept my days just barely within the legal limit). But I developed a deep affection for the country and learned a ton. I mean, did you ever think a gorgeous beach like this could exist in Britain? (The water IS cold. I’ll give you that.) Some of the most important things I learned during my time in the UK: “You all right?” means “How are you?”, not “What’s wrong?” Brits are masters of mocking those they love and being icily polite to those they hate. The food is pretty fucking great, and the desserts are on a different level (give me all the sticky toffee pudding and Eton Mess). Newspapers are left behind on the tube out of courtesy for others to read. And, um, the word fanny — you never want to say that word out loud here. ?? How did the UK surprise you?

Is it safe for a woman to travel alone in #Mexico? HELL YEAH. ???? Turn on cable news and you’ll have these images of doom and gloom — drug cartels and migrant caravans and violence and poverty. This news coverage is designed to rile people up — and this view of Mexico is SO UNBELIEVABLY DIFFERENT from what it’s actually like to travel in Mexico. ?????? I’ve traveled solo extensively in Mexico and today I’ve published a detailed guide to solo female travel in Mexico. It includes the things you actually need to worry about (water safety and noise) and what you don’t need to worry about (cartels and caravans). I hope you enjoy it. The link is in my profile and I would love if you shared it with any of your friends planning to visit Mexico soon. ? Have you been to Mexico? What’s your favorite spot? Share away!

Appearances can be deceiving. ?? Take a look at this photo — me relaxing in the sun, stretched out and catching rays in #HamelinPool in #WesternAustralia. The truth was that posing for this shot was TERRIFYING. I’m perched on a very narrow plank of wood, like a balance beam, and I’m engaging every core muscle I have so I don’t fall into the water, right on top of the stromatolites — some of the world’s oldest living beings that dwell in the water right below this platform. My pal @freiseindesign_lifestyle_blog grabbed the photo as quickly as she could and I rolled over slowly onto my left side, glad that I had balanced without falling into the Pool and risking their UNESCO World Heritage designation. Also, fun fact, this was taken right on the #TropicofCapricon. Kind of cool to do that. #seeaustralia #justanotherdayinwa Did you ever take a shot that was much harder to pull off than it looked?

I’m in a coffee shop right now, my favorite Danish import in Manhattan, the kind of place that plays loud music that builds and crescendoes until the beat DROPS and I’m wiggling my toes like mad because that’s the only socially acceptable here. I mean, this is New York, but this is also the Upper West Side.
?
This reminds me of 2015. 2015 was my most insane year of travel, the year that I was finally making good money and living on the cheap as I hopped around the world. Dancing on beaches from El Salvador to Montenegro to Thailand. Spending time with a variety of handsome gentlemen. Blogging only when I felt like it, and I throwing my extra cash into a when-I-get-to-New-York fund.
?
Then it all came to a halt in Chiang Mai. My body seized up and suddenly I was terrified to go anywhere I hadn’t been before. I ate breakfast at the same place every day because I was terrified what awaited me elsewhere.
?
I changed my ticket to fly home early. It was time.
?
Two months later, I moved to New York. It cost me $10,000 just to move into my apartment, let alone buy a life’s worth of non-IKEA furniture. Freewheeling was done. It was time to work.
?
It’s been a better life.
?
But sometimes I hear that dance music and I am back on the beach, hands in the air, my ghost self enjoying the party of a lifetime.

Sometimes I wonder if you look back at my old posts and can see the romances written between the lines.
?
I love this country BECAUSE OF WHO I GET TO SEE.
I get this country AND ONE PERSON IN PARTICULAR.
I love the food AND THE BREAKFAST HE MAKES ME IN THE MORNING.
I could live in this country AND MAYBE WE COULD ACTUALLY MAKE IT.
?
That’s a lot of love. And it’s not a lie. If I say I love a place, I do genuinely love it. But when a certain wonderful place is tied up with a certain wonderful someone, there’s a different level of passion that shoots out of my fingertips.
?
Looking back, smiling and settled in New York, I remember those past times with fondness. It seems obvious to me when a particular travel romance was blossoming. I wonder if it was obvious to you.

Three years in New York today.
Three years of being asked, “Still loving it?”
Three years of overwhelm.
Three years of opportunity.
Three years of hemorrhaging rent money.
Three years of ducking my head at showtime.
Three years I could have been bored in Boston, cliché in Bangkok, degenerate in Berlin.
Three years of wonder.
Three years of getting closer.
Three years of gratitude.
?
I made it. I’m still making it.
I will live here until I am dust.

I’ve discovered my new favorite getaway in #Mexico: the island of #Holbox. ?? What I most love about the island is that it has a fun and unpretentious atmosphere without being overtouristed. There are no chains or big-name brands. And guess what — in October they passed legislation banning single-use plastics and new construction on the island!! I am beyond happy to hear that — it shows that they’re preserving Holbox long-term instead of making a cash grab. ?? I wrote about my time in Holbox in today’s blog post, as well as my stay at the incomparable @casasandra boutique hotel — the link is in my profile. Hope you enjoy it! Thanks @bia1973 for the pic! ?? Have you ever been to a place that banned single-use plastics?

HAPPY UP HELLY AA! ?? It’s the last Tuesday in January — tonight #Shetland will be filled with Vikings yelling “YAAAR!” and setting a giant boat on fire! ?? I attended #UpHellyAa seven years ago (SO LONG) with @haggistours and to this day it’s my favorite thing I’ve ever done on my travels. Watching the Vikings throw the torches at the boat...watching the Vikings sing the Broadway tune “Enjoy yourself”...dancing with men in kilts until 8:00 in the morning. THE BEST TIME EVER. If you go, go with Haggis, because they have access that nobody else has, including tickets to the best party. Believe me, you want to go to the best party. ?? I’m going to quote the two Shetlanders on the street after a night of drinking: “Happy Up Helly Aa, ya couple o’pricks!” ?? Is this event on your bucket list?

Take me back to the place where the water looks like THIS. ?? This is #CaboCatoche on the island of #Holbox in #Mexico. It’s a 45-minute ride in a speedboat from the main beach area of Holbox — and it’s so worth it because LOOK HOW DESERTED THIS IS. Imagine if this were Koh Phi Phi and there were Maya Bay-level crowds around here. So I enjoyed it. I strolled. I posed (had to). And I enjoyed the most mellifluous escape from New York in January. Ha! ?? Did you go anywhere warm this month? Or are you stuck in the cold? Or are you laughing at all of us because you live someplace warm year-round?

UH OH. ?? The other day I walked into a brand new coffee shop in Manhattan and discovered THIS setting. It felt like a Wes Anderson hotel lobby! Brightly saturated teal along with shell pink decor. The coffees were delicious — they even made a smoked coffee beverage and they have taps for all kinds of milks. So why did I initially panic? BECAUSE THIS IS THE NEXT INSTAGRAM HOTSPOT AND NOBODY KNOWS ABOUT IT YET. So, do I mention its name and watch it explode? Or do I let it happen naturally, as it inevitably will? Or do I do the gross and selfish thing and go take my own photos before revealing any info? I don’t know. Edit: it’s @felixroastingco! ?? Do you ever wrestle with revealing cool places on social media? This is honestly the most conflicted I’ve felt over a place to date.

Ever thought of traveling #Antarctica solo? I did and loved it. ?? Now, I don’t mean going off on a raft completely on your own and living in a tent among the penguins. That’s just for scientists (and they are badasses). What I mean is signing up for an Antarctica expedition on your own — no travel companions or buddies, just you on a ship full of strangers. It may sound scary or intimidating, but it shouldn’t be. Tons of other women were doing the same thing (most of them in their forties and fifties) and you’ll make tons of friends no matter what! Plus, I think that it’s best to experience Antarctica solo, so you can breathe the continent in without being distracted by a partner. I talk about this in my latest post — link in profile. Hope you enjoy it! ?? Would you travel to Antarctica solo?

June 4, 2019. 
Turned 40 today. It’s hard moment. Halfway point. Reassessment day. Now I realize what a midlife crisis is all about. 
But the world always throws in something you don’t expect. A nest in my backyard. Brand new life that I’ve been looking at for weeks. A new beginning. 
#nature #40thbirthday #birds #nest #robin #nest #wildlifeconservation #midlifecrisis #homeiswheretheheartis

Whale shark and a ballerina. 
Not something I usually see at the same time. 
These images are part of a larger project I’m developing dealing with habituated animals - creatures normally wild, that are used to, or influenced by human interaction.

Masai Mara, Kenya | October 14 2018
My brood. @marvilacar and I are not really sure if all this is lost on the boys. When we were 5 feet away from the lion, KK was yacking it up about The Flash and whether he’s faster than a cheetah. Mateo kept asking about the remake of the Lion King as an elephant strolled past our truck. They still get excited about a “closet built inside the walls” at our hotel (we only own IKEA)... so I’m not really sure what will really stick with these kids. Thanks to @natgeowild @safariliveofficial  @maniejohnkipas for the opportunity to bring the kids to this open air classroom in the Maasai Mara. Follow @bonetiredmama on IG for BTS of our trip and @marvilacar and @benlowy for some photos and videos from The Great Migration. #bealpha @sonyalpha

Masai Mara, Kenya | October 2018
Lessons from the field. 
So lions will mate for the whole day but the actual coitus lasts for only about 5 seconds. Then the male sleeps for around 15 minutes before trying again. This will go on for the whole day. Why is he called King of the Jungle again? @benlowy and @marvilacar  are on an expedition in Kenya for Nat Geo Wild Thanks to #safarilive for their hospitality! ©?Lowy+Lacar #natgeowild #thegreatmigration #dinnertableconversations #homework

New Blog Post! While in Norway ???? I was honored to spend a few days deep in the arctic tundra with a Sami family who allowed me to be immersed in their lives as reindeer herders (it's not an easy job!). The winter migration cabin was an hour and a half snowmobile ride into the wilderness, had no running water, electricity was ran by a generator that had to be cranked every morning and we woke up to -25 degree Celsius temperatures ?? The head of the household, Nils, woke up in the wee hours every morning to tend to the herd of 700 and spent the evenings chopping firewood, smoking meat and/or fetching water from the river. But still he would go on to tell me, multiple times, that he had the best job in the world. That is passion ??????
.
Read my story about the memorable experience on the blog (link in bio) ??
.
??: In this photo Nils wife, Oddbjørg Hætta gave me the privilege to borrow her traditional gákti ????
.
Many thanks to @VisitNatives @ImpactTravelAlliance @VisitNorway and @flynorwegian for making this trip possible ?? #VisitNorway, #FlyNorwegian #thisissustainable

Walking down one of the cutest street in Oslo ???? It’s lined with adorable and colorful homes (an instagrammer’s dream ??). This is just a preview of all the great things to see and do in Norway’s capital city. There are trendy restaurants, a gorgeous opera house, a royal palace and the Oslo Fjord Sauna where you can take the icy plunge into the fjord like me! ???? Plus, in 2019 the city was named the Green Capital of the World ?? ?? @visitnorway @VisitOslo #VisitNorway
.
PS: I got to Oslo on a convenient and comfy flight ?? aboard Norwegian Air, which—by the way—was ranked as the most fuel-efficient transatlantic flight! Are you sensing a sustainability trend here?  #thisissustainable @flynorwegian  @impacttravelalliance #FlyNorwegian

These huskies were eager to run the dogsled trail as soon as we walked through the @trastiogtrine gates ?? They happily barked and jumped with the excitement of the anticipation. The best part was that you could tell that these pups were treated with the respect and love ?? they deserve, which is so important when choosing a dogsledding company. #VisitNorway
.
Have you ever been dogsledding? ?? ?? I’ve been before but this time was different because we got a list of our team, then had to find and harness the dogs. Plus we took turns actually being the musher!

Doing an ice plunge in the chilly Fjord is a very popular pastime in Oslo (they believe its good for circulation and the heart ??). And the Oslo Fjord Sauna is the perfect place to combine wellness with a bit of adventure! The idea is to sit in the sauna, a floating shed made of reclaimed driftwood and designed to overlook the beautifully architectured Opera House, until you are so hot that you can’t wait to jump into the water ????
.
I wasn’t in Norway for more than two hours before doing this jump into the fjord, though for me it was less of a jump and more of a backwards climb down the stairs—not sure which way was the better technique ??
.
Would you take this icy plunge? .

TIL DEG??
I kveld har jeg lyst å fortelle deg hva som ligger bak mine |reklame innlegg. Nemlig min historie....
Jeg skal ikke ta deg med på en sympatireise, for det har aldri vært min greie, men jeg deler for at jeg ønsker å vise deg dette. Da jeg over natten for snart seks år siden mistet alle mine krefter, og fikk min ME diagnose, ble jeg påtvunget en helt ny måte å leve livet mitt på. Jeg brukte store deler av dagene mine på sofaen eller i sengen, og det var fra her jeg delte noen av mine første bilder på Instagram. Det ble mitt lille fristed, som jeg kunne være sosial uten å føle meg annerledes  eller at det tappet meg for unødige krefter. Sammen med bildene jeg delte, prøvde jeg også å beskrive hverdagen min, slik den var på EKTE. Det var nok ikke så vanlig på den tiden , men kontoen min vokste likevel og jeg fikk mange gode vennskap. Etter to år vokste også interessen fra ulike firmaer seg større og større. De ønsket at jeg skulle bruke deres produkter i bildene jeg delte fra hjemmet mitt. Dette var starten på mitt eget foretak CC-Styling. Jeg kunne for første gang på veldig lenge, kjenne at jeg hadde mulighet til å jobbe igjen, men på en helt ny måte. Med god hjelp fra min egen mann og en egen regnskapsfører, takket jeg ja til mine første samarbeidspartnere. Det var så skummelt, men samtidig enormt stas og gøy! Jeg takket kun ja til dem jeg selv kjente i magen at var riktig, og jeg selv kunne stå inne for 100%. Denne kontoen skulle ikke være noe annet enn MIN og den skulle fortsette å være personlig. Og det tror jeg du som følger meg, føler det samme om i dag. Samtidig som jeg er så takknemlig for at DU er her, er jeg også så STOLT over mine samarbeidspartnere. De gir meg full tillit og muligheten til å jobbe med det jeg ELSKER, på den måten jeg behersker. Jeg kan ikke ha en 8-16 jobb, og jeg har enda en veldig begrenset arbeidsevne, MEN jeg kan jobbe! Og nettopp det har gjort at jeg har lært meg å takle denne tilværelsen. Jeg føler meg så heldig som får lov å kalle meg selv en influenser, og er ydmyk til tusen! Så vit det neste gang du ser et reklame innlegg fra meg. Jeg er her med hjerte og deler med den største takknemlighet. Klem Renate??

Savner du engasjement under bildene dine?
Eller er du lei av å kommentere på den samme stuen om og om igjen? Da har jeg noen tips til deg, som kanskje kan gjøre noe med både engasjement og motivasjon??

1. Mulig det er på tide å droppe «Ha en fin kveld» eller «Happy Friday» som eneste tekst under bildene dine. Dette gir ikke mottaker så mye å spille tilbake på, annet enn et fattig «Ha en fin kveld du også» Og vi havner ofte i «fellen» hvor vi enten bare skriver «så fint» eller rett og slett, scroller forbi. Vi mener nok å ønske hverandre en fin kveld, men det blir litt gjentakende og kjedelig etterhvert. La oss være ærlige!

2. Lag gjerne en tekst som sier noe om det du deler bilder av. Feks med dette bildet mitt her, tenker jeg alltid på gjestene mine som er forbeholdt dette rommet på hytta. Da kan jeg skrive noe om hvilken funksjon rommet har, og hvilken stemning jeg ønsker å skape for gjestene våre. Materialvalg, farger osv

3. Still gjerne dine følgere et spørsmål under bildet du deler. Et spørsmål fra det du deler eller fra noe annet som kanskje har med dagen og gjøre. Feks Har du noe spesielt du pleier å gjøre for dine gjester? Eller har du noen planer for helgen? (Hvis det nærmer seg helg) 
4. Synes du det er vanskelig å finne på noe å skrive om, da det er det samme kjøkkenet du deler bilder av igjen? (Vi opplever alle dette????) Lag en liten, gjerne litt personlig, tekst fra dagen din. Da byr du litt på deg selv , og lar oss bli bedre kjent med deg. Og kanskje du plutselig starter/byr på en morsom dialog under bildet. 
5. Denne er til deg som skal kommentere under bildet. Hvis du er lei av å skrive det samme, eller ikke vet hva du skal skrive, så ta tak i teksten som står under bildene. Da skaper du en mer personlig dialog og viser at du bryr deg og leser under bildet. Det er også himla mye mer moro å skrive en tekst med mening, enn et fattig «så fint» hver gang. Stol på meg?? 
6. OG så er det jo helt lov å scrolle forbi, det er helt lov å «kun» dobbeltklikke! Dette er kun ment som en forlengelser av det som ble startet hos meg i går. Med å finne tilbake motivasjonen , skape engasjement og å gi litt mer LOVE her inne??
Klem fra Renate??

Du finner meg her i kveld, hvor jeg skjenker meg litt ekstra Instalove tid?? Etter dagens tilbakemeldinger å lese, er vi flere som vil gjøre det fremover. It’s a burrata-filled chile relleno, stuffed inside a breakfast burrito (with chorizo, home fries, eggs, salsa and other stuff). But Instagram is weird and people don’t read captions anymore and I’m too busy chasing my kids to care, so call it whatever you want and have a wonderful day.

One of my favorite childhood memories is coming home from school or soccer practice to the sound of metal utensils clanging and scraping against the sides of a wok as my dad cooked alongside recorded (VHS!) episodes of Martin Yan's "Yan Can Cook." My dad was an incredible cook, and obsessed with the flavors of Asian cuisine in particular (also, I was never allowed to touch his Chinese cleaver). So, in honor of him — and because grilling season has arrived and you're desperately in need of another go-to recipe — I partnered with @KikkomanUSA and @Allrecipes to make a dish I know my dad would love.
-
This Honey-Glazed Chinese Chicken is crazy delicious and the recipe, featuring the iconic Kikkoman® Teriyaki Marinade & Sauce, is so simple. I like to bake these drumsticks about 3/4 of the way through and then finish them on the grill just before serving. Serve with grilled veggies, on top of rice or noodles, or even pull off the chicken and use as a filling for tacos or lettuce wraps. Also can confirm: The marinade works just as well with wings or boneless chicken thighs.
-
Grab the recipe on Allrecipes.com
--> https://www.allrecipes.com/recipe/216966/honey-glazed-chinese-chicken/
-
#CookingWithKikkoman

I used to think the Porchetta Melt (w/ rapini, caramelized onions and fontina) from @gjustabakery was the perfect sandwich. And then my wife brought one home and I added a fried egg and a lot of calabrian chili oil... and now my opinion has changed.

Pro tip: Don’t wait until your 30s (with two hyperactive kids) to get your wisdom teeth taken out. It’s just a terrible idea. My two saviors, however: The NCAA basketball tournament, and — after a couple days of yogurt, bone broth and applesauce — savory oatmeal. Honestly, it’s the only way I’ll eat oatmeal. My favorite version, pictured here, starts with steel cut oats and includes soy sauce (or liquid aminos), spicy chili crisp (or any type of chili oil), furikake, chives and an egg yolk. Once I was mostly recovered and graduated from baby food, I started adding vinegar-cooked greens like bok choy or Chinese mustard greens. And if you’re not cool with the raw yolk thing, a poached or fried egg works just as well.

For Valentine’s Day, I made @mysequinlife a dish inspired by a Mario Batali recipe I saw back in the day... which is ironic considering he’s an all-around turd of a human being and treats women like shit. But anyway, this is a loose interpretation of “tortellini en brodo” w/ chicken sausage and kale. I cooked the tortellini in a Calabrian chili-tomato broth, tossed in a bunch of kale and the cooked/crumbled sausage and then finished it with pecorino, olive oil and more Calabrian chilis (because my wife is a spicy Italian and also likes her food that way). I took this pic during Round 3 of our leftovers, and as with most soups it gets better as it sits. So, make a large batch.

If my Indian power lunch concept “Naan Negotiable” doesn’t pan out, got this idea for a Middle Eastern boozy hangover brunch spot called “The Struggle Israel.” Thoughts?? Signature dishes would be things like za’atar fried chicken & falafel waffles w/ aleppo honey, shawarma breakfast burritos, open-faced lamb burger benedicts on pita w/ harissa hollandaise... oh, and also the Shakshuka Tacos pictured here [to make, I started with 1 lb of chorizo (pork, chicken, soy... whatever), added a few handfuls of chopped kale and swiss chard, then chickpeas, poured in the prepared shakshuka sauce, and cooked it down until it was “taco-friendly” (i.e. less saucy than a normal shakshuka). I finished it with crumbled feta, cilantro and the obligatory runny egg... which, for these tacos, I cooked separately in ghee as opposed to poaching in the sauce].

Need some holiday dinner inspo? How about Orecchiette w/ Sausage and Broccoli Rabe... served family style in a skillet... with BURRATA. This is my go-to (not authentic, I’m aware) version of one of my favorite all-time dishes... the burrata gets stirred in at the table just before eating and instantly melts to create a creamy, cheesy sauce. Bonus: There’s just enough red and green in here for it to officially qualify as “Christmas pasta.” Recipe below!
-
1 lb. Orecchiette pasta
2 tablespoons Extra Virgin Olive Oil (plus more for garnish)
1 lb. Italian-style pork or chicken sausage
3 garlic cloves, minced
Crushed Calabrian chili flakes (can substitute red pepper flakes), to taste
1 bunch broccoli rabe, stems trimmed and leaves chopped
Sea salt, to taste
Juice and zest from 1 lemon
1/2 cup freshly grated Pecorino or Parmesan cheese
1/2 cup bread crumbs, store-bought or homemade
8 ounces burrata cheese (if it’s a ball and not scoopable, cut into small pieces)
-
1. Cook pasta in a large pot of boiling salted water, according to package directions, just until ?al dente?. Reserve the pasta water.
2. Meanwhile, heat oil in a heavy large skillet over medium heat. Add the sausage, garlic and chili flakes and cook, breaking up the sausage with a spoon or potato masher, until browned. Transfer sausage mixture to a plate.
3. Add broccoli rabe to the same pan and sautee for 2-3 min, just until tender. Deglaze with a cup of reserved pasta water, scraping up any browned bits from the bottom of ?the pan?.
4. Add sausage mixture and pasta to ?the pan? and stir well to combine over low heat, adjusting the consistency with more of the reserved pasta water, if needed. Season to taste with salt.
5. Remove from heat and stir in lemon juice and grated cheese. Place burrata cheese in the center, then top with bread crumbs, lemon zest, more chili flakes and a drizzle of olive oil.
6. Bring the skillet to the table and, while still hot, toss the burrata until creamy and stringy and the pasta is completely coated. Divide the pasta among shallow bowls and serve with extra bread crumbs and chili flakes on the side for guests.

If you’re cruising around NYC today and see a guy in a dad costume double-fisting pita sandwiches, it’s probably me. Feel free to say hello. [“Cauliflower Shawarma” and “Harissa Falafel” pitas from @taimfalafel].
When that natural light is so good, it makes the burrata melt... [margarita pizza + hatch green chilies from @emmysquaredpizza]
If you guessed Spicy Pork Meatball Benedict on brioche, you'd be 100% correct. #MeatlessMonday
Some people like their crepes with Nutella and fresh fruit. That’s cool. I prefer mine handheld and stuffed with Peking duck, egg, kimchi, hoisin, chili paste, crunchy wontons and cilantro.

Hi ??????? Heading to NYC this week and obviously looking to keep that winter diet going. I’ll be hopping back and forth between Manhattan and Brooklyn, so if anyone has suggestions on food, drinks, romantic spots for married couples to make out, etc... please send them my way! ???? [pictured: everything bagel with pastrami salmon and scallion cream cheese from @russanddaughters]

Your Thanksgiving leftovers are probably long gone by now... but just in case, here’s an idea: Mashed potato waffle (roasted garlic-parmesan) with turkey carnitas, jalapeño chimichurri and a fried egg. Wouldn’t be mad if you just ladled some leftover giblet gravy on top instead of the chimichurri... or maybe a chipotle hollandaise if you’re into the whole benedict thing. Clearly I’m trying to keep things on the lighter side this holiday season.
Family, food and football (and hopefully lots of sleep). Basically all the best things. Happy Thanksgiving, everyone. #ForeverThankful ????

Having a little too much fun in the work cafeteria today: Chinese BBQ pork (Char Siu) breakfast sandwich with avocado, fried egg and spicy hoisin sauce on a toasted pretzel croissant.  Co-workers are staring. ??

Just a friendly reminder that you should probably be making an extra batch of stuffing this week. Also, if there's one week out of the year to dust off that waffle iron, it's this one [btw this is my go-to chicken apple sausage & cornbread stuffing with caramelized onions, and I added a handful of shredded gruyere to the mix before waffling].
The Thanksgiving Week all-potato diet starts... now [coal-roasted Yukon potato w/ poached egg, bacon, aged gouda, creme fraiche, chives].

Toasted Coconut. Pretzel. Peanut Butter.  I try not to play favorites with my homemade nut butters... but this one, as the wife would say, is beyond. Delicious with apples, spread on toast (also: stuffed inside of french toast), stirred into yogurt or ice cream... or eaten straight out of the jar with a massive spoon. I wrote down a recipe. Here you go:
?????????
1 (16 oz) jar roasted peanuts, unsalted or lightly salted
2 cups mini pretzels (regular or gluten free)
1 cup shredded unsweetened coconut
Honey or Agave (optional)
Sea Salt
?????????
1. Preheat the oven to 350 degrees F. Toast the coconut for 5-7 minutes, or until lightly golden brown. Let cool for 10 minutes.

2. Place peanuts in the bowl of a food processor and process for approximately 5 minutes or until creamy and smooth, scraping down sides as needed.

3. Add pretzels, toasted coconut and honey/agave, if using, and pulse several times until desired texture is reached — you still want to see and feel bits of pretzel and coconut. Taste and add salt, if needed (will depend on which peanuts are used and personal preference).
*
[another option for the above step is chopping the coconut and pretzels by hand, and then stirring them into the peanut butter along with the honey/agave — adding sea salt at the very end, to taste]
*
4. Store in an airtight jar or container at room temperature for up to several weeks (trust me though, it’ll be gone well before then).
?????????
