2018: Year of the Rotisserie Chicken? I sort of hope so, because I probably ate enough fried chicken this year to hold me over for the next decade. Btw this version from @rtrotisserie in SF is one of the best I’ve had. Ever. So good I (almost) forgot about those housemade chimichurri, chipotle yogurt and BBQ dipping sauces. Next time I’ll go by myself, or make the wife get her own chicken.

Spicy cauliflower tortillas: That guilt-free solution for stuffing your face on #TacoTuesday (also, every other day). Had a lot of requests for the recipe after my previous post... so, I skipped work, locked the kids in their rooms and ignored my wife for most of the day just so I could write down this recipe and share it with you. It's cauliflower, eggs and a few seasonings (I included my favs, but feel free to do your own thing). These are soft, very pliable and fold just as well as most corn tortillas. And they’re healthy and stuff, which is kinda cool in moderation.
•
1 head of cauliflower, cut into florets and stems removed
2 eggs
1-2 canned chipotle peppers in adobo sauce, seeds removed, finely chopped (can subtitute 1 tablespoon good quality chile powder)
1/4 cup freshly grated cotija or parmesan cheese (optional)
1 teaspoon lime zest (optional)
1/2 teaspoon dried oregano (optional)
salt and pepper, to taste
•
1) Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
2) Add the cauliflower to the bowl of a food processor and pulse until texture is similar to rice (even a bit finer, like couscous)
3) Transfer cauliflower rice to a microwave-safe bowl and microwave for 2 minutes. Stir, then microwave for another 2 minutes and stir again.
4) Place the cauliflower in a cheesecloth or dish towel and squeeze out as much water as you can (be careful, it’s hot)
5) Transfer drained cauliflower back to a bowl and add remaining ingredients. Mix until well combined.
6) Separate the mixture into 6 equal sized balls, then spread each onto a parchment-lined baking sheet to make 6 flat circles.
7) Place in the oven to bake for 10 minutes, carefully flip each tortilla, then return to the oven for an additional 5 to 7 minutes. Let cool slightly.
8) Heat a cast iron pan over medium heat. Place tortillas in the pan, pressing down gently until lightly golden, 1-2 minutes per side.

Fact: When using cauliflower tortillas, one can justifiably consume twice as many tacos. These are stuffed with braised turkey thighs (Thanksgiving leftover ideas!), roasted mushrooms, vinegar-cooked greens, avocado, feta and spicy chimichurri sauce and served on homemade red chile cauliflower tortillas [I add puréed chipotle in adobo and grated cotija/parmesan into my tortilla mixture, which automatically makes them the best ever].
Why does this Kimchi Bacon Cheeseburger with fried egg and gochujang mayo look like it’s about to spit the hottest verse of 2017?

Pro tip: If you’re going to go through all the effort of making spicy fried chicken sandwiches [w/ horseradish cheddar, pickles, buffalo sauce and avocado ranch on a @kingshawaiian bun] ... you should probably make a few extra and stash them in the fridge. They reheat really well in the waffle iron, and you’ll be extremely grateful the next time you and your significant other drink several bottles of wine and can barely get out of bed (see: today).

Sometimes you prepare a meal, and then take several photos of said meal in order to satisfy your twisted food fetish. Other times, you dress up your entire family in food costumes and politely ask someone else to take pictures while you watch. I have problems. Happy trick-or-treating, everyone.

The “Pescado Zarandeado” from @coniseafood: In my opinion, still one of the single most epic dishes in all of LA. Butterflied and grilled whole snook served with caramelized onions, fresh tortillas and a side of spicy green (jalapeño) sauce. It’s a very messy and equally satisfying make-your-own-fish-tacos experience. Also, I believe this is meant to be shared. I never share. Get your own fish.

“Shu-mai, don’t bother me...” [fun fact: I sing and/or hum that ?? self-written remix literally every time we’re eating dumplings and the shumai hits the table... and every time, my wife shakes her head in embarrassment/regret. Obviously doesn’t realize my #dadjokes are all that and dim sum ??].

Ate a ton of amazing food this past weekend in Seattle. Didn’t post or even take photos/video of 99% of it. I have to say, it was pretty liberating. Also discovered that I prefer warm food over cold food. That said, the one time I felt obligated to pull out my phone (in the pouring rain) was for @corazontruck... and specifically these Vampiro tacos w/ carne asada, melted cheese, avocado salsa, smoked chile mayo, cilantro and onion on a crispy handmade tortilla (yeah, these dudes are making all the corn and flour tortillas from scratch in the truck). Some of the friendliest guys you’ll ever meet, and some of the best tacos I’ve had outside of LA.

Still the best burrito I’ve eaten all year (because homemade is always better): Breakfast burrito with Dungeness crab fried rice, Chinese garlic spinach, caramelized kimchi chorizo (Kimchorizo™), soft-scrambled eggs and Oaxacan cheese, rolled up tightly and pressed in the cast iron with coconut oil.

In honor of #NationalPastaDay, a loose interpretation of what is possibly my favorite all-time pasta dish: Bucatini all'Amatriciana. This one starts with a spicy tomato sauce (and a LOT of pancetta and garlic), and I finish it with pecorino, smoked olive oil and an egg yolk... which is all just a more eloquent and socially acceptable way of saying: I made bacon, egg and cheese pasta.

Because I once read in a book somewhere that eating spicy, sweat-inducing foods actually makes you feel cooler (literally and figuratively), here's a Quinoa Chicken Curry Bowl to help beat this October heat. It's loaded with braised chicken, eggplant, tomatoes, garlic, ginger and garam masala... and topped with brown rice, crushed almonds and cilantro. No butter. No cream. It's Indian food with less attitude [bonus: my kids love it].

Packed the wife a lunch today (then made her take a photo with it, obviously). Here’s the shaved turkey sandwich w/ chipotle gouda, smashed avo, lettuce, tomato and spicy greek yogurt caesar dressing on grilled country bread. You know you did it right when the avocado is seeping through the holes in the bread.

My go-to brunch strategies: 1) Order the most unique item on the menu 2) Order one of everything on the menu. Basically did both at @greatwhitevenice, with the most unique dish being these corn fritters with charred avocado salsa, green chiles and a poached egg [and if you ask really politely, they’ll stack a few thick slices of grilled halloumi cheese on there].
Still the best $5 lunch/dinner/2am meal in LA. Don’t fight me on this. #NationalTacoDay ??

Late Saturday nights call for Sunday morning Waffled Bao breakfast sandwiches. Steamed Chinese BBQ pork bun (Char Siu Bao), cut in half, stuffed with scrambled egg + cheese + caramelized kimchi + hoisin + sriracha... pressed in the waffle iron (with fingers crossed). If you don’t have access to fresh or frozen Bao, store-bought biscuit dough works just as well [use two biscuit rounds, roll out or flatten with hands, layer fillings on one biscuit round, top with second and pinch all the way around to seal before pressing in waffle iron on medium heat].

Because Cuban-Japanese fusion is so hot right now [heavy sarcasm] ... here’s my Katsu-Cubano sandwich (aka The Katsubano™). It's layered with traditional chicken katsu, honey ham, swiss cheese, pickled cucumber-wakame salad, jalapeño mustard and katsu sauce on panini-pressed ciabatta. 2018: Year of the Dog... and #Cubanese cuisine.
Confirmed: These spicy lobster nachos remain one of the single most satisfying ways to crush your diet (and wallet) while at @disneyland.

Whenever I act a bit childish (rare), dive into a plate of food with reckless abandon (often), or laugh uncontrollably at my horrendous #dadjokes (never, because they’re all awesome), my wife asks if she’s married to a 5-year-old... and I’m like, “uh, I don’t know... are you?” She never changes the number. We’ve been together 16 years, and I’m still 5? Doesn’t add up. Anyway, today this dude turns 5 and I couldn’t be more jealous... or more proud of the little man he’s becoming. Happy 5th birthday, buddy. Welcome to the club.

When in San Diego, one must @getcrackshacked. There's literally nothing on this menu I wouldn't order (salads included), but my go-to is the "Firebird" sandwich: Spicy fried thigh, cool ranch, crispy onions and pickles on a potato roll. I added a generous layer of their housemade Kimchi BBQ sauce underneath the chicken... because it was there and seemed like the right thing to do.
Will drive for #SpicyPie. This should hold me over until Coachella 2018. @kaaboodelmar
Things I order 100% of the time if on the menu: Crispy ahi tuna tacos with avocado and spicy mayo [not pictured: the first order of tuna tacos].

Portobello "benedict" with garlic spinach, oven-roasted yellow tomatoes, poached egg, basil pesto-creme fraiche, aleppo pepper, meyer lemon zest and smoked sea salt. In the weeks leading up to our recent trip, as sort of a mock anniversary gift to myself (and my wife, let's be honest)... I challenged myself to get back down to my wedding weight from 10 years ago. I (mostly) cut out carbs, cheese and alcohol, and hit the gym almost every day... sometimes twice. The results: 20 lbs in 30 days, actually surpassing my goal (and then I went to Greece and ate gyros for two weeks). Is that diet sustainable for me? Clearly not. But I had the discipline to do it... and I saw major results... and I didn't die or severely injure anyone. So that has to count for something. #30DayAnniversaryChallenge [start the movement].

My camera roll is currently jam-packed with gyro and souvlaki pics like this... which is what happens when you eat an average of like 2.3 per day for two weeks. We had some excellent versions of this Greek street food staple on the islands, but I still think the best (and also: worst) gyro and souvlaki can be found in Athens. Fittingly, the chicken and pork gyro seen here were the final meal of our trip. It's also one of the few times we ate them completely sober and before 2am [free food photography tips: Natural lighting + Sobriety = Superior quality photos]

If you've been following my stories, you know I have a thing for places that are off the beaten path. This breakfast spot in Mykonos was a bit of a hike, but such a hidden gem... and these soft-scrambled eggs with truffles, avocado mousse and roasted cherry tomatoes on housemade wheat toast were some of the best I've had from a restaurant (although I could've done without the random enoki mushroom). The secret to getting that creamy consistency: Greek yogurt! Can't wait to get home and give this a go in my kitchen. Actually, I'm in no rush to get home, but when I do...

The first time @mysequinlife and I tried octopus was 10 years ago in Mykonos. It was braised in red wine, and so incredible we ordered another one for dessert. The massive piece of octopus pictured here (from @scorpiosmyk) was cooked sous vide, marinated in Greek olive oil and herbs, and then charred on the BBQ. It was spork tender and completely perfect. Hard to say if it's the best I've ever had, but certainly top 3.
How to hack a Greek hotel breakfast buffet: Open-faced sandwich with bacon, roasted tomatoes w/ melted gruyere, spicy tzatziki and a fried egg on toasted country bread.

???? In case you are wondering: no, this moon hasn’t been by no means photoshopped there and you see its actual size
.
Most of you might know by now that I usually plan my shots really in advance. Well, this time it wasn’t that case. I was catching the morning flight at Tromsø airport and I saw this big fat setting full moon almost at sunrise. I took this shot handheld (leaning on a window) with a 600mm lens because I had already checked in my luggage with my tripod in as well ???????
————————————————————
.
————————————————————
????En caso de que alguien se lo pregunte: no, esa luna no ha sido puesta con photoshop y estáis viendo su tamaño real
.
Muchos de vosotros sabéis que suelo planificar mis fotos con bastante antelación pero este no es el caso. Iba a coger el primer vuelo de la mañana en Tromsø y ya en la puerta de embarque vi esa luna gigante poniéndose justo antes del amanecer. Hice la foto a pulso (apoyado en la ventana) con un 600mm porque ya había facturado el trípode dentro de la maleta ???????

There are around 10,000 breeding pairs of puffins on Skomer and Skokholm Islands, making them one of the most important puffin colonies in Britain. They arrive in mid-April to nest in burrows, many of which have been dug by the island's large rabbit population. The last puffins leave the island by the second or third week in July. They feed mainly on small fish and sand eels; often puffins can be seen with up to a dozen small eels in their beaks flying back with food run across the walkways oblivious to the tourists

Java, Indonesia
…………..
#wonderfulindonesia #tripofwonders
—————

—————
????Have you ever been inside an active volcano Caldera?
.
It’s just an amazing experience I will never forget. You have to wear a gas mask and even so you finally end up breathing a lot of sulfur since the air is so corrupted. Then, if you are lucky as I was you can see blue flames due to the high temperature of the combustion. It’s really a unique natural phenomenon
.
I was brought there by @indotravelteam, the perfect tour operator for this adventurous journey
————
.
————
????¿Habéis estado alguna vez dentro de la caldera de un volcán activo?
.
Es un experiencia que nunca olvidaré. Hay que llevar una máscara antigás y aún así acabas respirando algo de sulfuro porque el aire está muy cargado de ello. Una vez allí, si tienes suerte como yo, puedes ver llamaradas de fuego de color azul, debido a la altísima temperatura de combustión del volcán. Realmente es un fenómeno único en la naturaleza
.
Gracias a @indotravelteam por llevarme allí. Es el perfecto tour operador para este tipo de aventuras

.
Q: Did you know that lotus flowers close their petals at night?
—————
.
—————

Como estaba “petado” de gente usé mi objetivo más luminoso para desenfocar el fondo y llevar toda la atención a la flor de loto del primer plano
.
Y hablando de flores, ¿Sabíais que la flor de loto cierra sus pétalos de noche?

??Mount Bromo view point, South Java, #wonderfulindonesia ????
—————
??: EOS 5d Mark IV + 70-200L @canonespana
—————
.
—————
????Got into a van for a 14h ride + almost 2h by ferry after a crazy party in which I had to kiss goodbye a bunch of good friends. Had a wake up call at 3am and bundled up for a hike in the most absolute darkness.
.
No matter how tough having gotten there could have been, everything made sense as soon as the sun rose in the horizon. I would definitely do it again 1 million times if I ever could see these views one more time
.
If you are traveling through Bali you might want to go Bromo with @indotravelteam, a 100% recommendable tour operator. They offered me a taylor-made tour to Bromo and Ijen.
Everything was perfect, try it!
—————
.
—————
????Estuve 14h metido en una furgoneta más casi 2h de ferri después de una fiesta loca en la que me tuve que despedir de grandes amigos y compañeros. Me levanté a las 3 de la mañana forrado de ropa para hacer una caminata en la montaña en la más absoluta oscuridad
.
Da igual lo duro que resultara el llegar allí, todos dejó de importar en cuanto el sol asomó por el firmamento. Lo volvería a hacer un millón de veces si pudiera volver a contemplar esas vistas una sola vez más
.

Did you know that people who eat avocados tend to be healthier than people who don’t? I can’t think of a better reason to make this Chocolate Avocado Pudding! ????
•
According to the results from the National Health & Nutrition Examination, which observed over 17,500 participants, avocado eaters tend to weigh less and and have a significantly lower risk of metabolic syndrome compared to those who don’t eat avocado. (This study also noted that people who eat avocados tend to eat more veggies than those who don’t, so I’m sure that has a lot to do with these results, too!)
•
I’ve been making this avocado pudding for nearly 10 years and I’m still surprised by how much I love it— and that’s coming from someone who doesn’t *love* avocados. In this updated post, I talk about more benefits of eating avocados and some alternative ways to sweeten it, too!

When you have a picky eater, smoothies are a helpful way to get some leafy greens, or veggies that they wouldn’t otherwise eat, into their day. They don’t even have to know about it! •
My kids do help me add handfuls of fresh spinach to our smoothie most mornings, so they don’t seem to mind, but I think it helps that they know they won’t taste it! ??
•
Other veggies that you can sneak in without detection? Frozen cauliflower and sometimes frozen broccoli (if the smoothie has a strong tropical flavor). Kale can NOT be “hidden” if you ask me. My kids can taste kale, and so can I. I don’t mind it, but it’s not fooling anyone. ??
•
If you want one of my go-to recipes for kids, use the link in my profile to get it! Or you can use the search bar on my website to find my post on smoothies for babies and toddlers.
•
I’ve shared a link to this cute reusable pouch in my blog posts, too! I’ll put a swipe up link in IG stories if you want to check them out. They are BY FAR the best pouch we’ve ever used— going 5 years strong!
•
Tell me, do you try to sneak anything into your smoothies? I’ve gone through all sorts of supplement experiments, like spirulina and collagen, but right now our go-to protein addition is just plain hemp hearts! I love that they are a complete source of #plantbased protein, without a chalky texture.

Up until this year, my kids would hunt for eggs, see the candy and try a piece, and then forget about it the next day. It was perfect! ??????
•
This year, my 5-year-old remembers everything, so I’m not getting off that easy. We let him choose ONE piece of candy each day, to avoid the “forbidden” appeal of it, but boy does it affect his behavior! ?? He has had crazy mood swings this week and doesn’t want his usual meals, so we are going to conveniently RUN OUT of candy this weekend. I’m done!!
•
If you’re a parent, how do YOU handle Easter candy & egg hunts???
•
I think stickers, slime, little toys, or even coins are the way to go for filling eggs! It would be so much more fun to make a healthy treat together in the kitchen, without crazy sugar crashes later. But maybe that’s just me?! ?????

You may be surprised to hear that when I travel, I'm always on the lookout for the best donut in town. Not the best “healthy” donut, but THE. BEST. DONUT. around. ?????? When I was in New York last weekend, I tried several different places, including this one from @levainbakery
•
I mention this because I don’t want my Instagram account to come off as if I only eat healthy food 100% of the time. I enjoy creating healthy recipes that are EASY and TASTE GOOD, so that’s what I share here most of the time, but I also want you to know that I’m human, and I do still reach for things like donuts, french fries, and potato chips. (And pizza!) ??
•
I allow myself to eat EVERYTHING because, for years, I struggled with binge eating. (For at least a good third of my life!) In my case, it was triggered by dieting and a struggle with perfectionism. If I "slipped up" during a diet, I was off the wagon for the rest of the day— and often times for the rest of the week, eating to the point that I was uncomfortable because I knew those foods would be off-limits to me again in the future. It’s not a fun way to live, always being “on” or “off” a diet. ????
•
The only way I was able to finally stop this miserable cycle of yo-yo dieting was to also STOP feeling guilty about eating certain foods. Your pants size won’t change from eating one donut or going out for pizza with your friends. It’s what you do MOST OF THE TIME that counts, and it’s easier to make good choices when your brain isn’t clouded by arbitrary diet rules.
•
If you have struggled with something like this, I hope you’ll find a similar sense of food freedom! You can read more about how I stopped binge eating by clicking on my profile link ( @detoxinista ) and then clicking on this photo.
•
And tell me— is there a certain food that YOU seek out when traveling?? Let me know! ??

•
Quinoa is a “super seed” because it’s a COMPLETE SOURCE of plant-based protein, containing all of the essential amino acids the body can’t make on its own.
•
One thing to know about quinoa is that you must soak it to remove its bitter flavor for recipes like this one. It doesn’t take long, but it makes a big difference in the overall taste! I like to top mine like I would regular cereal out of a box— with some almond milk and fruit.
•

I'm always on the lookout for a salad that's fun and flavorful. ?? Whether that's adding caramelized onions, creamy dressings, spiced nuts, or some punchy chopped fruit. While delicious, Caesar salads are drowned in dressing and covered with cheese. So I’ve partnered with @wholefoods in the spirit of the the New Year to show you #HowIJanuary and I’ve remixed this classic salad to help you enjoy it in a new and delicious way. I pared down your typical Caesar to still offer all that creamy goodness with a vegan dressing, some gluten-free croutons, and I swapped in shaved brussels sprouts because they're a good source of fiber and hold up in the fridge for a few days. Follow the link in my profile to find more gluten-free options for you to add to your meals! #Sponsored #MakesMeWhole

Here's the recipe below:

RECIPE:
Brussels Sprouts Caesar Salad: -2lbs. brussels sprouts, shaved thin on a mandolin or with a sharp knife
- drizzle extra virgin olive oil
- squeeze lemon juice
- fat pinch salt
-1 ripe avocado, sliced
- gluten-free croutons (optional)
- walnuts shaved on a microplane, to garnish (optional) 
Dressing: -1/2 c Plain Kite Hill Greek-style yogurt
-1 tablespoon lemon juice
-1 tablespoon apple cider vinegar
-1 1/2 tablespoons nutritional yeast
-2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
-2 teaspoons capers
-1 clove garlic, grated on a microplane
-Salt & pepper, to taste
-1/4 cup plus 2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil 
1. Toss shaved brussels sprouts with the olive oil, lemon juice, and salt.  Use your hands and mix everything together for about 1 minute.  Set aside.
2. Make the dressing.  In a food processor fitted with a metal “s” blade, combine the yogurt, lemon juice, vinegar, nutritional yeast, Dijon, capers, garlic, and salt and pepper to taste.  With the machine running drizzle in the ¼ cup of olive oil until everything is combined.  Remove the lid and check the dressing, if it’s too thick, add the extra 2 tablespoons of olive oil and combine once again.  Taste and adjust salt if needed. 
3. To the shaved brussels sprouts, add roughly half the dressing and mix.  Taste, and add more dressing and salt if needed.  Top w/ sliced avocado, gf croutons & shaved walnuts

Regardless of the season, I always keep cookies on hand. I’ve teamed up with @wholefoods to show some of my favorite picks for the New Year and this recipe is one of my all-time go-to options. I particularly like having these almond butter cookies around –they're full of fats from almond butter, and they're made with monkfruit sweetener, which can replace added sugars. But they totally fill the 3-4pm void when I need a cookie! Get the recipe for these delicious babes below!  #Sponsored @wholefoods #HowIJanuary #MakesMeWhole
RECIPE:

Almond Butter Cookies: - 1 1/4 cups almond butter
- 1/2 cup monkfruit sweetener
- 1 large egg
- flaky sea salt, for topping 
1. Preheat oven to 350°F and line a cookie sheet with parchment paper.  Set aside.
2. In a large bowl, mix together the almond butter, sweetener, and egg until thoroughly combined. 
3. Using a cookie scoop, or by hand, portion the cookie dough into 1 ½ tablespoon balls and place them on your cookie sheet leaving about an inch between each cookie.  Using a fork, gently press the cookies cookies down making an imprint. 
4. Bake the cookies for 12-14 minutes.  Let cool completely before eating. ??????

Getting back to the basics with my typical grocery #wholefoodshaul for about 3-4 days. I’m teaming up with @wholefoods to show you my favorite staples for the new year. 
Buying all of our groceries and prepping for an entire week has never worked for us. Instead I buy groceries for 3-4 days.  Our schedules inevitably shift and change depending on the week, so this little system actually saves us money and our food never goes bad.

???????? Last week, a bill was signed into law in Georgia that is a near-total ban on abortion. This marks the fourth “heartbeat” law to be passed in the United States in the last year - a name that is designed to be emotive. It refers to the first signs of the development of a heart in a fetus at 6 weeks of pregnancy, long before most people know they are pregnant.
?????????
???? Georgia’s bill stands out for going one step further in including personhood language, criminalising not just abortion providers, but also pregnant people for having abortions or even miscarrying. Today, Alabama passed its own law banning abortion except when the health of the mother is at risk. We remember that Savita Halappanavar died in Ireland with the same law on the books.
?????????
?????? Currently, women & pregnant people living in Northern Ireland are forced to travel to mainland Britain for abortion care that is illegal in their home country. There will always be people who cannot travel because of domestic violence, immigration status, and disability. People living in Northern Ireland and the USA deserve the dignity of accessing safe, legal & local reproductive healthcare at home. #nowforni

These laws won't stop women and pregnant people from having abortions, or from making the best decision for their bodies and families, it will just mean they are forced to do so unsafely and with stigma. #reproductiverightsforall ?

Please join me in supporting @plannedparenthood @womenhelporg @all4choice @abortionsupportnetwork ?????????

With the awareness generated by #metoo, there is an increased demand for support services as more people are emboldened to name what happened to them.??Rape Crisis Centres??offer much-needed support to people who have been assaulted across England and Wales (@rapecrisisew), but demand way outstrips supply.??This time last year, there were 6,355 survivors on Rape Crisis waiting lists and these can be as long as 14 months.?? This means that if a survivor calls to look for support they may be turned away...
?????????
???? Successive UK governments have failed to fund life-saving services. There are just 44 Rape Crisis Centres in England and Wales. ?? But the Istanbul Convention (which our Government will soon ratify) sets out a minimum provision of support for victims of rape which would require that there be 150 Rape Crisis Centres in England and Wales. ?? It’s simply unacceptable that a country like mine falls so far short of the minimum standards set across Europe.
?????????
??????? So on #IWD2019, I encourage you to sign Fern’s petition ????LINK IN BIO????and demand that Theresa May guarantees sustained ?? funding for rape crisis support services, ?? so the survivors of sexual violence can access the support they need. ?????????

???????? #Repost @gloriasteinem “3rd edition out today with a new foreword by my dear @emmawatson. I had a lot of fun updating it, hope you’ll feel the same reading it!”
?????????
???? “Why do I love Gloria’s writing so much? She makes what otherwise can be arduous and depressing reading, into something not only relatable but enjoyable...She believes in personal testimony - the sharing and passing on of women’s stories...She uncovers things that are obscured by today’s conditioning and normalizing which when exposed, are absolutely fascinating...Her plain common sense - calling things out as they are - will make you laugh out loud...
?????????
Sometimes the world she envisions seems so far out and impossible to me or just wildly optimistic. But I have come to believe it is through radical feminism and the radical nature of Gloria’s message, that the job of equality will get done. I used to think the citadel didn’t have to topple. Now I believe it just might and should, and that we need to let old ways of being die for something new to be born. This book contains ideas for that new road, even though some were written almost forty years ago.
?????????
People have asked me what the feminist movement needs to succeed. A new word? More men involved? I would rephrase the question. What obstacles need to be removed for us to succeed? In order to win our full humanity, in life, we have to confront the biggest superpower in the world: the patriarchy...
?????????
I never liked the idea of being a rebel. I played Hermione Granger, for goodness sake, who once famously compared the notion of being expelled to death! I remember thinking my first detention was the end of the world. But of all the things to fight for, I’d say freedom and respect are pretty good ones! And if I can do it with, and in the wake of, women like Gloria, all the better. And actually, as Hermione and I learned, being disruptive was quite fun after all.
?????????
So, have your mind blown, laugh out loud, think in new ways, get angry, feel the feminist affinity...This was the first collection of feminist writing Gloria ever published...I hope they become as precious to you.” ????

???? Here’s an excerpt from the powerful November & December @oursharedshelf letter written by Brittney Cooper (@professor_crunk) & Rebecca Traister.
?????????
“Dear Our Shared Shelf Readers,
?????????
We are honored to be able to begin a conversation with you about the power and consequence of women’s rage, both personal and political. We could not be prouder or more excited that Audre Lorde’s Sister Outsider, Brittney Cooper’s Eloquent Rage: A Black Feminist Discovers Her Superpower, and Rebecca Traister’s Good and Mad: The Revolutionary Power of Women’s Anger have been selected as the Our Shared Shelf books for November/December 2018.
?????????
The famed feminist activist, poet, and essayist Audre Lorde was one of the foremost thinkers on the importance of anger. In her essay, “The Uses of Anger,” which you will get to read in her book Sister Outsider, she wrote, “every woman has a well-stocked arsenal of anger potentially useful against those oppressions, personal and institutional, which brought that anger into being. Focused with precision it can become a powerful source of energy serving progress and change.”
?????????
To encounter these words is to be changed by them. We have been changed by them. And we hope that women’s anger, put to use within progressive coalitions in which fury is expressed and treated as instructive, will in turn have the power to change the world.
?????????
In this period, as we reckon with the rise of hard right authoritarian regimes around the world, many determined to roll back human rights—the very freedoms generations of angry women before us worked to win—today’s women are again being called to embrace our rage–its force, its potential, its messy complications. The fight against global patriarchy is far from over. Violence abounds but so does the possibility of building a new world from the wreckage of the old one.”
?????????
???????? You can read the rest of their letter here: tiny.cc/OSSLetter

?????? I am excited to announce that July/August's pick for @oursharedshelf is our first poet, @rupikaur_ , and her book of poems Milk and Honey ????. Rupi Kaur is an Indian-born, Canadian-raised poet and artist. She chooses not to use upper case letters or punctuation in her poems as an ode to her native language, Punjabi. She travels the world, including recently to her native country India, performing her poems and drawing crowds of hundreds. Both of her books, Milk and Honey and The Sun and Her Flowers, have made the New York Times bestseller list, which for a poet, is astonishing.
•••
Over my lifetime, I have fallen in and out of love with poetry. Performing poems was what got me into acting (I had a primary school teacher that made everyone learn one a week, and eventually I won a poetry recital competition!) In secondary school and at university, I loved deciphering the codes of poems in class discussion, but I honestly wondered if poetry would continue to feature in my life outside of an academic context.
•••
Enter poets like @holliepoetry, @SabrinaMahfouz and Rupi Kaur- I demolished whole books in single sittings. Unlike poems I have often spent weeks unraveling, Rupi’s poems are not designed to obscure meaning or entertain too much ambiguity - they hit you like punches to the stomach. They are immediate, visceral and not easily digested. I am loathe to say Rupi has made poetry “accessible” because while this is the truth (Rupi’s poems and illustrations fit well into those famously square shaped Instagram frames), there is nothing easy or accessible about what Rupi chooses to talk about. In fact, the topics she chooses, are audacious.
•••
Here is a 25-year-old girl saying the unsayable… to hundreds of thousands of people: that she has been raped, that at times she has been abused, that she bleeds. And sin of all sins… she actually likes the hair that grows on her body. Yes. She actually thinks it is beautiful. And that she is beautiful as God made her - what a transgression. That her body is her home and nobody else's.
•••
Full letter on: www.goodreads.com/oursharedshelf

The magic of Venice Carnival! ????
—
Modeled after ancient Greek and Roman festivals, Carnival was a holiday that allowed regular citizens to dress up in anonymous costumes and make fun of the aristocracy without fear of retribution.
—
But it eventually backfired, allowing criminals to get away with all kinds of crimes behind the masks, and Carnival was banned in 1797. The celebration & parties returned though during the 1960’s.
—
Wandering through the confusing alleyways and canals of Venice this week with colorful characters like this was so much fun! ??
—
#carnevale #venice

I’ve been snowboarding for about 25 years now. I started as a kid, and grew up just 30 minutes away from two ski resorts in New Hampshire. I’m forever grateful that my parents introduced me to skiing & snowboarding at a young age. I was never a big “team sport” kinda guy, but boy did I love racing down a mountain in the snow!

And I took a year off before starting school to be a backcountry ski-bum in Montana, working nights as a short-order cook and snowboarding 5 days a week in the winter. It’s official. I’m an Irish Citizen now! ??
-
This past year I went through the legal process of obtaining Irish citizenship. Because my Grandmother was born in Ireland, I was able to claim citizenship by descent through a special law. It took about 9 months, and cost about $700.
-
As a dual citizen of the United States and Ireland, with two passports, I can now travel or live in the European Union without restrictions.
-
Did you know that about 40 million Americans have Irish ancestry? Many of their ancestors traveled to the United States from the port city of Cobh, pictured here, looking for a better life abroad.
-
Now more and more American/British citizens are applying for Irish Citizenship, as a hedge against the craziness and ultra-nationalism going on in the world. Giving themselves another option, just in case. ??
-
If you’re interested in reading about how I became a dual citizen of Ireland, check out my new blog post, linked in the bio. ????

Got a lot of questions about my Afghanistan trip after the last post.
-
Yes, you can travel to Afghanistan. Women too, although I’m not sure I’d recommended it alone.
-
No, I don’t recommend it solo for most people. It’s what I’d call a “black diamond” destination. Like how they rate ski slopes. You need to work your way up to it.
-
This is a trip I’d been planning for years. Following local news. Tracking down obscure trip reports. Talking to others who’d been recently.
-
For example, the border between Tajikistan & Afghanistan sometimes closes without warning. For days, or weeks. Which would leave you stranded, as the road to Kabul is too dangerous.
-
The Taliban is only 20 miles away. Last year, they captured the border town area (that I entered from) for 2 weeks before being kicked out again.
-
The Wakhi people, like this man, were very welcoming and friendly. However there are less nice people not far away. The situation is constantly changing.
-
And travel in Afghanistan is tough. Just getting to the start of my trek took 2 days of driving through deserts and rivers with multiple breakdowns. Meals were basically flat bread, warm sour yak yogurt, and if you’re lucky, some goat.
-
Just wanted to share a bit behind the scenes for what went into this trip!
-
There are a few adventure tour groups that visit the Wakhan (check Google) which would make things easier. I passed one of them as I was leaving the mountains. The region does see about 100 tourists every year.

The ancient tomb of an Afghan tribal leader and his family, decorated with Ibex horns and red cloth flapping in the wind.
-
Trekking 100 miles through the mountains of #Afghanistan was one of my most memorable adventures to date! If you’d like to see more photos from this trip, go visit my blog ExpertVagabond.com
-
Wakhan Corridor, Afghanistan

Bar hopping in the streets of Ireland! ?? (Galway)
-

Tre Cime di Lavaredo is one of the most iconic hikes in the Italian Dolomites. It’s a pretty easy 6 mile loop with incredible views, but not much elevation gain.
-
Italian authorities have started restricting vehicle traffic into the Dolomites during summer months at Sella Pass, allowing only 350 cars per day (previously up to 5000 cars a day made the trip). It’s a new attempt to curb the massive amount of day-tripping tourism, and help save their stunning environment.
-
However local restaurant and hotel owners are upset, complaining it will drastically reduce their income, and visitors will simply use a different mountain pass, sending the tourism dollars to other areas. It just goes to show there are no easy answers to solving this problem!
-
?? @anna.everywhere

#sustainabletravel #dolomites

Is Instagram & #SocialMedia ruining travel?
-
The massive growth of social media and travel blogs in recent years has had a profound impact on how we travel. Not all of it positive. As someone who makes a living inspiring others to travel, this topic has been on my mind a lot lately.
-
I think overcrowding and bad behavior have always been a part of the travel experience. But a combination of population growth, a larger worldwide middle-class, the explosion of digital photography, and efficient social media tools for expressing our already narcissistic nature are making things worse. What do you think?

Goodbye California, hello Texas!
-
After a year of living in Los Angeles, @anna.everywhere & I have decided to move on. While I was surprised at just how much I ended up enjoying LA, we've decided it’s just not for us long-term. It’s a bit too crowded, a bit too expensive, and a bit too dry.
-
So we’re hitting the road again, this time for a temporary move to #Austin, Texas. We’ll be there for a few months before moving on to our ultimate destination, which I’ll keep secret for now (just for fun). ??
-
I thought I’d be able to slow down and plant some roots somewhere, but we seem to just keep moving regardless. Maybe this is the curse of being nomadic. That after moving so much, over so many years — what’s the big deal with moving once more? I guess moving once a year is better than once every few months, so there’s still hope!
-
Anyone have tips they want to share about Austin? I hear we need to try some BBQ... ??

Welcome to the Grand Canyon of the Pacific! Waimea Canyon on the island of #Kauai is 10 miles long, and up to 3000 feet deep. Can you believe this is Hawaii?!
-
The colorful mix of red volcanic earth and green jungle is really impressive to see in person. Not to mention all the waterfalls… had a lot of fun hiking around here capturing images of this landscape. ??

Is this the most beautiful place in the world? The steep emerald-green cliffs of Kauai's Na Pali Coast will take your breath away! Massive waterfalls, pristine beaches, and lush tropical valleys. It’s basically the definition of “island paradise”. ??
-
The only way to experience this 17 mile stretch of rugged coastline is by hiking the Kalalau Trail (unfortunately it was closed due to landslides during our visit), by boat, sea kayak, or helicopter. I’m still buzzing on adrenaline from this open-door helo flight...

The sun beats down mercilessly, setting every color around me ablaze – and since everything is blue, I feel like I’m walking above the clouds in a mythical sky kingdom.
-
But this is no myth, it’s #Chefchaouen. Located in Northern Morocco, the city’s signature color is a variety of calming shades of blue that lower your blood pressure in seconds.
-
Known as Morocco’s “blue pearl” or “blue city”, the buildings in Chefchaouen are painted using a talc or chalk-based paint that looks so beguiling.
-
Exploring a labyrinth of narrow blue alleyways smelling of spice, incense, flowers, and fresh oranges — was one of the highlights of my journey to Morocco. Plus it’s a photographer’s dream!
-

Sunset mission in #Florence! Ponte Vecchio is the only bridge over the Arno River the fleeing Germans didn’t destroy in WWII.

The Duomo, or cathedral, of Florence Italy is MASSIVE. Construction began in 1256, but took almost 150 years to complete. A pair of bronze doors created by Italian artist Lorenzo Ghiberti are regarded as one of the first major works of the Early Renaissance period.
-
The cathedral area is often packed with tourists, but if you get there before 8am, it’s relatively quiet. It’s a popular place for wedding photoshoots too.
-
Anyone else enjoy visiting religious landmarks, regardless of the denomination?

Sainte-Chapelle is a gothic royal chapel built by King Louis IX of France to hold his collection of Christian relics, including Christ’s “crown of thorns”.
-
The stained glass walls were insane! Each panel depicts a different scene... 1113 of them. It took 7 years to build it all.

Ooh la la! Finally made it to the Eiffel Tower. Built for the 1889 World’s Fair, this 1063 ft (324m) tall structure has become one of the most recognizable landmarks in the world.

Happy New Year (Nyepi) from Bali ?? 
Today I want to give thanks to this beautiful island & it’s people for always welcoming & providing me such a wonderful home away from home for the past 2.5 years ?? 
Nyepi is the Bali day of silence- meaning complete silence (no fire/light/electricity, no work, travelling- even the international airport shuts down, no entertainment & fasting) 
Its a very special time to be here on the island & witness this celebration as the island is purified ???? #Bali #Indonesia #Nyepi

I’m so thankful to have learnt so much about the complicated topic of captive elephants in Thailand, there’s so much more depth to the issue than we see on the surface, and I truely admire the work @anantara_goldentriangle & @gtaef_thailand are doing for the cause! It was my first visit to the north of Thailand & I wanted to visit an elephant camp that I would feel confident in their ethics, If you have the opportunity to visit this resort I certainly recommend, but also if you are visiting other camps/ sanctuaries be sure to research as much as you can before you visit! Recipe in my bio guys.

What's not to love about this bad boy dish!! And what's even better is this recipe is now on my website!! Good old toad in the hole. With dirty gravy this is not something you'd eat every night but what a treat to end the weekend with. Happy Sunday guys x #WeekendCooking
Jamie's Comfort Food p34 | super schnitzel. You can use any meat for this one! Tasty and tender, serve with pickles and a potato salad and you've got yourself a winner! Happy Saturday guys x

Get this one sorted today and enjoy this weekend! Homemade prune & armagnac ice cream makes for treat on warmer days like today and hopefully the weekend. The recipe is on p334 in my Jamie Does cookbook.

Love the work that @migratefuluk are doing. Supporting migrants on their journey to integration through the power of cooking and cookery classes. Hit the link in my bio and getting following @migratefuluk to find out more and read about the inspirational stories of some of the people they've already worked with. #RefugeeWeek

Bucatini amatriciana. Although not from Rome originally, this has become one of the city's most famous pasta dishes. Delicious and super simple to make. Feel free to use smoked British pancetta or bacon instead if you can't get your hands on any. Recipe on p114 of #JamieCooksItaly.

20 years since "The Naked Chef'' and I think it's fair to say a lot has happened in that time. Naturally its a moment of reflection and so when @channel4 said they wanted to create a show looking at my 20 year journey, I knew @davinamccall would be the best person to guide me and the audience through it all. Its been an absolute pleasure to work with her, invite her into my life and just talk. I hope you all enjoy looking back with me and Davina, remembering the amazing times, talking about the tough time and looking at the future too. Watch out for '20 years of The Naked Chef: Jamie bares all' out later this year everyone... JO xx

A steaming bowl of #veggie chilli. You can't beat this stuff whatever the time of year! It's definitely up there as one of my favourite go-to veggie meals!!! What's yours?? #MeatFreeMonday #MFMcountMeIn

I call this 'cheat's pappardelle' as you can cheat by cutting your own pappardelle from ready-made fresh lasagne sheets! The flavours from the slow-braised leeks and crispy porcini pangrattato will make your tastebuds scream with joy! Find the recipe on p333 in Jamie At Home. #RecipeHack #TopTip

Avocado on rye bread many, many delicious ways...
From the classics combos of eggs, cream cheese, and spinach to more adventurous topping ideas like beetroot, houmous and cottage cheese, turn to p38 in my Superfood Family Classics cookbook for some fresh #breakfastinspiration.
My deliciously fresh trapani-style rigatoni can be sorted in 30 minutes, perfect for a laidback dinner! One of the favourites from 30 Minute Meals cookbook - p40 if you've got x.

This kind of Sunday... perfect roast chicken!!! A tasty and easy family recipe, perfect for the weekend. Recipe in my bio if you need it x
#SundayRoast

One for tomorrow guys, your #SundayRoast all in one pan! Tray-baked pork chops with herby potatoes, parsnips, pears and minted bread sauce... still one of my favourites from my Return of the Naked Chef cookbook! If you've got the book, flick to p180 for the recipe.

New one on the website for you guys, my cassoulet de Essex. With herby and crispy breadcrumbs this a beautifully comforting dish to try this weekend. For maximum flavour, make the flavoured salt and rub it into the meat the day before and leave in the fridge to marinate. Link in my bio. #ComfortFood #WeekendFeast

Strawberries!! Now in season across the UK. Sweet or savoury, there are so many ways to enjoy!! Just as they are or blitzed in a cocktail, cooked in a crumble, reduced into a jam, rolled in a roulade or chucked into a salad. What's your favourite way to enjoy these lovely people???

Start your day right with my avocado on rye toast with ricotta cheese, strawberries, pine nuts and a drizzle of thick balsamic vinegar!!! Honestly guys these flavours work so well together. Get the recipe and loads of other topping ideas on p41 of my Super Food Family Classics cookbook.

One from the archives... This is not a chip butty as you know it guys, a healthier version, but it tastes just as good!! P84 in my Super Food Family Classics cookbook, this one will blow your mind. Cheesy sweet potato, avocado and ketchup!! One to try!

My #veggie ramen with walnut miso, kimchee and topped with a fried egg. A meat free Monday winner from my Everyday Super Food book - p190 if you've got it.

Frozen fruit has so much potential. Blitz with equal measures of yoghurt in a food processor, add a drizzle of honey, then freeze and you've got yourself a delicious homemade ice cream alternative. Perfect for warmer days like today. Full recipe on p266 in my Save With Jamie cookbook.

BBQ British ribs. Cooked low and slow, these ribs take their time but it's worth it if you want all the flavour. It's one of those dishes you can't rush. One to try over the weekend. Simply serve with a potato salad and radishes. Recipe link in my bio ??

This asparagus, eggs & French dressing dish is one from Quick And Easy Food. All you need is 5 ingredients and it's ready to eat in just 15 minutes, plus you'll have leftover dressing for another lunch. Over on p164 in the book.
#QuickAndEasyFood
Using spelt spaghetti, vine tomatoes and ricotta, this easy traybake has a lovely nutty taste and is perfect for a mid-week dinner. It’s on P160 in my Everyday Super Food book.

You won't want to miss this #QuickAndEasyFood recipe... Speedy spiced prawn soup. A brilliant combo of aromatic rice and a sweet prawn broth!

All you need is 5 ingredients:
250g small frozen cooked peeled prawns
150g basmati rice
8 spring onions
2 heaped tablespoons korma curry paste
1x 400g tin of light coconut milk

#QuickAndEasyFood aubergine penne arrabbiata… a fuss-free fiery #veggie pasta with attitude! Ready in under 30 minutes and only 5 ingredients:

12 fresh mixed-colour chillies
2 aubergines (500g total)
300g dried wholewheat penne
4 cloves of garlic
1x 400g tin of plum tomatoes

Sensational Italian seared beef… that’s what you call romance on a plate! 
You ONLY need 5 ingredients, that's #QuickAndEasyFood:

1 tablespoon pine nuts
250g rump steak
2 heaped teaspoons green pesto
40g rocket
15g Parmesan cheese

While there are much bigger problems happening in the world, suffering from acne for me was debilitating. It’s something that I’ve dealt with since I was a young teen and has caused me to feel anxious, helpless and insecure. As humans, I don’t think we share our insecurities enough because we live in a time where being “perfect” is the standard. We curate our life online and pick the pretty moments to post. I’d like to show a younger generation that not everything is perfect. Being insecure about my acne gave me thick skin but I wouldn’t ever wish that feeling upon anyone so after trying countless options, I found something that has been helpful in maintaining clear skin for me. It’s been a long journey but I’m excited for where my skin is now. I didn’t think I’d see the day where I would feel confident posting a makeup free picture. My goal is to open up a dialogue around skin positivity. ??

#FollowMeTo the colored houses of old Stockholm on Stortorget square. We are in love with Swedish concept of life Lagom. Lagom means the harmony of internal and external, the perfect balance between work and rest, translated as "just right". This harmony has been preserved in the attitude of man to nature. In Sweden, people are serious about the environment, trying to save nature, and they are the first one who use innovations that go to the benefit not only man but also the environment. @oriflame_ru

#followmeto Dagestan Babaku mountain with @natalyosmann. First I saw this mountain on the countless photos of our friend photographer who travels across Dagestan @photo_shapiev (by the way he takes amazing pictures on the nature of Dagestan and the remote villages). So since then I have decided that we must visit this place and climb this mountain. At that time I wasn’t doing my 10 000 steps a day program, so my stamina wasn’t at it’s best :) (now as you can see I am a perfect athlete almost competing in Iron man contests in my dreams). We took some horses there, which was a challenge, since they don’t really have horses and we had to ask local shepherd to bring them. Having called him like 10 times before arriving there to make sure that he has 9 horses we were under impression that the plan was finalised and we would arrive to the bottom of the mountain and then try climbing it. 
When we arrived there somehow the shepherd was a bit surprised that we came, even though we called him twice the night before. Somehow he only brought 4 horses so we had to minimise our group. So the trip full of adventures had started. Babaku mountain is one of the few in the world that has a pyramidal peak. You won’t find a lot of information about this mountain online though because of it’s remote location. Height of the mountain is 3997, but some adventurous people from what I heard - piled several stones up so that it would reach 4000m. Don’t think that this counts by the officials though :)).

#followmeto to abandoned village of Gamsutl. I must say that seeing a picture of this village online was one of the motivations for me to travel across Dagestan region. It is translated from the local Avar language as “at the foot of the khans fortress. In 50s people started to leave this village for a better life and it became abandoned. Nobody wanted to return to this place, nobody except only one person, and old man Abdulzhalil. He came back there around 13 years ago. His relatives tried to take him back to the bigger villages, but he always returned. He even called himself “Mayor of Gamsutl”. For several years he tried to revive this village, but unfortunately 3 years ago he had died. Nevertheless if you are ever in the area of Dagestan, this place is definitely worth visiting.

#followmeto the land of Dagestan with @natalyosmann. We are starting to share content from Dagestan, Russia and it is  extremely important for me as I was born in this region in a city called Makhachkala. #followmeto the Luxor Temple of Man with @natalyosmann. We are finally starting to share amazing stories from our trip to Egypt. Stay tuned for one of the best videos we ever shot and for more photos! Also will be sharing IG TV episodes from each day! 
This temple was built by Amenhotep III, but completed by other pharaohs of Egypt. Towards the rear is a shrine dedicated to Alexander the Great. During the Christian Era, the temple’s hypostyle hall was converted into a Christian church and the remains of another Coptic church can be seen to the west. Then for thousands of years, the temple was buried beneath the streets and houses of Luxor. Eventually the mosque was built over it. This mosque was carefully preserved when the temple was uncovered. By the way the right Obelisk which is absent on the picture has been taken to Paris in 1830 to Place de la Concorde

I remember my first time I felt like I had found queer community: it was the summer before my senior year of high school, and I went to New York to study art at Parsons. The Sunday that I arrived in NYC, June 29 2003, was coincidentally the same day as New York City pride. The first person I met, Joe, and I decided to walk over to 5th Avenue and watch as the parade came down the street. More than anything, that summer served as an intensive in giving me understanding, language, and a sense of belonging in my own identity. I learned about and fell in love with the work of Catherine Opie, I spent afternoons at the piers with friends, I went to see Rent on Broadway with my friend Ojay, and knew that I was just beginning to figure out how expansive queer culture, and love, and relationships, and community can all be. I was enormously privileged to have that experience at 17 years old, and I know first hand how powerful and transformative it can be to have a supportive network of peers and mentors as we navigate our individual identities. In the spirit of that discovery, I'm proud to work with @fossil in support of #HMIxFossil #MakeTimeForGood. This pride month, Fossil is supporting the Hetrick Martin Institute with 100% of proceeds on the sale of their Live in Color watch going to HMI - the largest organization supporting LGBTQ youth and their families. As we celebrate 50 years since Stonewall, and 40 years since HMI opened it's doors, I want to aim the spotlight on the important organizations doing this work not just during Pride month, but all year long ???

Okay, so... I’ve been getting a LOT of questions lately talking about what many have affectionately referred to as “the girls” or ?? or ???? — so, let’s talk about it! They appeared basically over night when I was in the 5th grade and I genuinely never had a “training bra phase” because I went from pre-pubescent and flat chested to a D cup before I could even really understand what these body changes meant. I now wear a 36H and while I like my body on most days, I’ve also thought about breast reduction since I was a teenager, and still wonder how it might change my life. As for bras - I have and love SO MANY and am so grateful there are more beautiful options now than there ever have been in my lifetime. And finally, going braless (like I am here) is very, very new to me - and to be honest, I kind of love it, even though it’s also a bit intimidating and I feel like I’m breaking a LOT of rules, (and maybe those rules are kind of oppressive and rooted in respectability politics, anyways). Lots of tangents, here, but I get so many DMs about bras and cleavage and what to wear with XYZ that I figure, why not talk about it all in one place? Anyways, if you need bra recs, or tips on how to ditch them, or are struggling with boob sweat or something, leave a comment below and I’ll do my best to share my not-so-secrets with you, cause boobs are great (if you want them!) ?? @taylorkrausecreative

I’ve had a hard time thinking about anything else these last few days. Access to reproductive healthcare, choice, and the right to abortion is a PUBLIC HEALTH issue that disproportionately affects POC, low income communities, and the most marginalized among us. Over night, Missouri joined 5 other states that passed supposed “heartbeat” bills - restricting access to reproductive healthcare at a timeframe before most people are even aware they may be pregnant. It’s so important to understand that this is not about “saving life” and never has been: it’s about control. If it was truly about saving life, we’d be investing resources into sex education, access to contraception, healthcare, childcare, welfare programs, parental leave (all of which we SHOULD be investing in, btw)— but we all know that, right? I know I live in a bubble - one that sometimes feels safe and separate from what’s happening “over there,” but this feels scary and I feel it’s my responsibility to speak now, stay vigilant, and use the platform I have to encourage awareness around this issue. If you have the means, please consider donating to @aclu_nationwide, @yellowfund, @prochoiceamerica or one of the many local funds supporting access to safe reproductive healthcare near you. I also recommend following @ihartericka @pieraluisa @sarahsophief who have much smarter things to say than I do about this. (Image via @refinery29)

“FLAWS” ARE SOCIALLY CONSTRUCTED. I’ve been thinking about this question all day. Can we talk about this?? ETA: I assume good intent here and that the use of “you” is reflexive — so don’t worry about me being offended bc I’m not. But I DO want to talk about and explore the idea of flaws and what we deem to be a flaw or perceive as flaws within ourselves or others. The idea is designed to MAKE US feel small, less than, less powerful than we are. I think it’s important to examine who is deciding certain things are flaws and WHY. So. Let’s talk about it. What are the things you’ve been made to feel are flaws? Are they?

YOU’RE A WORK IN PROGRESS. KEEP EVOLVING. — I’ve put together 33 things I’ve learned in 33 years and consciously or not this was #33. You can read my other 32 in the link in my bio. ? PS: it’s definitely not meant as advice — every person’s path, healing, choices, etc are their own; it’s just a collection of things I’ve picked up over the years and wish I picked up sooner.

Boss talk ahead: One of the shadow sides of business is that entrepreneurship can feel like a tremendously isolating experience. As much of a blessing and a privilege as it is to be among the “firsts” in a field, it can also feel totally overwhelming to hear “no” over and over and stay motivated to keep pushing forward. I feel lucky to have an incredible business partner (seriously, some days I think if it weren’t for having each other, we would have quit before we started) and a growing community of founders and entrepreneurs around me, but I still definitely have days where I go through a series of existential crises  and question everything. Turns out, the questioning is actually part of an entrepreneurs growth process, in and of itself, and that it’s FAR from an isolated experience. @mailchimp’s new podcast Going Through It features stories from people like Samin Nosrat, Hillary Clinton, and Soledad O’Brien on a pivotal breakthrough moment in their lives. The first episode I listened to featured my friend and fat, queer, body-positive yogi @mynameisjessamyn, and it actually brought me to tears listening to her words echoing my own experiences. I’m starting this work week with a piece of wisdom care of Samin: “Say yes to no -- if you say yes to everything, then you can’t focus on anything.” AMEN. ?? @lydiahudgensphoto #MailchimpxRefinery29 #ad

TGIF, amirite? Lots of new faces around here - so allow me to (re)introduce myself, and hopefully I can get to learn a little bit about some of you, too. My name is Nicolette (sometimes Nic, rarely Nikki, NEVER Nicole). I’m a Los Angeles native and moved to NYC in 2004, and for the last few years have split the majority of my life between those two cities. I’m a Taurus, Leo rising, Libra moon - and am celebrating my 33rd birthday very soon. I’m very, very gay and for some reason that still surprises people.  I love color (even though I wear black on most days), pugs, and would choose tacos or sushi over almost any other foods. I think pink is a neutral. I started my career as a brand strategist and designer, and started blogging around that same time as a hobby - which eventually, somehow, lead to working in fashion media - including being a contributing editor and columnist at Marie Claire for 5 years. I co-founded @premme.us with my bff and biz partner @gabifresh, where we make some bad ass clothes for size 12+ babes. I love to laugh, and try to learn something new every day. Ok, that was a lot — YOUR TURN.

In 2019 we are shedding the remnants of the internalized fatphobia we’ve been carrying, (or at least I am). I’ve had this coat for at least two years (maybe 3? @gabifresh modeled it in their look book and I fell I love with it instantly); it’s been taking up space in my closet (which is truly precious real estate) and I have... probably never worn it outside. Every now and then I have to check in with myself on the ways I try to minimize myself and my body, so in 2019 I am really consciously working on NOT DOING THAT. We deserve to exist in the world, command attention and visibility, to wear a big flamboyant fuzzy coat that exaggerates rather than “flatters,” and have fun - period.
Happy 2019 from the future!!!!

"Self-care" isn't all bath bombs and face masks. Trust me, I love a good bath and a solid moisturizing mask, but for me, self-care has become more about spreadsheets (hello, adulthood) and work-outs. Whether it's taking a walk around the neighborhood mid-day during work hours, or getting myself up before the crack of dawn to jump on a 6AM spin session, I've learned the importance of breaking a sweat in order to realign my body and mind. It is such a necessary part of my mental health routine! While I'm not really one for "resolutions," I do love goals - so I've been challenging myself to get active and move more throughout the day. My @fossil sport smartwatch allows me to set custom goals, and track them, that are actually realistic and beneficial for me - all while tracking my heart rate and allowing me to set little reminders like drinking more water throughout the day, too. What does self-care mean to you? #ad #fossilstyle

The theme for 2018 for me has been HEALING. Big time. It was important for me to heal (for me, how other people navigate their lives is entirely their choice) before opening up about my vulnerabilities and pain points. 2017 was one of the best years of my life professionally, but absolutely my hardest, most challenging year on a personal level - an imbalance that in and of itself felt like a confrontational rollercoaster. There were so many enormous shifts - I went through a separation, decided to sell and move out of the home we shared in LA, my entire career life shifted rapidly, I developed new autoimmune issues, and my whole world very quickly felt like it was upside down. I wasn’t ready to answer questions like “what happened?” — as if there’s a simple answer, or even owed that to anyone but myself. Some things are best kept private, but I will say: we’re still close and have a lot of love for each other. Then 2018 came knocking and I knew it was time to focus on rebuilding, all wabi-sabi and full of imperfections and transience and change. And I feel good, now. Really good. I’m more confident, stronger, more patient, trusting myself and my intuition more. I committed myself back to therapy, said “no” to more things to say “yes” to myself, spent more time with my family, learned how to ask for help and support and patience, and got really fucking good at crying it out and processing all my feelings. So many of my friends have been facing similar changes, and that sense of community and knowing I’m not alone has made all the difference - and maybe it will help for one of you to know you’re not alone, either. Not everything has to be forever to have still been a really good time. And hey, everyone gets hyper reflective this time of year, right?! Nothing but gratitude for this process ??

You know how I (and everyone, basically) always say “body positivity is a journey”? I’ve been echoing that back to myself on repeat recently. A combination of stress, a major shift in my routine, and the fact that I’ve PROBABLY replaced all the water I usually drink with coffee, have made me not really feel like myself these past couple of months, and even actively feel sort of... not great. It’s really bizarre to not recognize yourself when part of your job is to put yourself out there — and then feel so stifled that you accidentally stop doing it entirely. I was talking about this yesterday with a friend and had to really remind myself that the things we see or criticize or nit pick in ourselves are not things other people would ever even notice. Be kind to yourself, and if you’re going through it with weird self-image feelings, know that you’re definitely not alone!

Tratar de resumir una persona tan grande en pocas palabras como Gabo es una tarea muy difícil pero intentar recordar alguien como él es realmente muy fácil. Todos conocemos, millones de personas conocemos, la magia de sus libros y de sus historias pero pocos hemos tenido la fortuna de conocer la magia de la que estaba hecho él mismo. 
Yo en este sentido puedo considerarme una afortunada cuando a los 21 años - creo que tenía 21 años cuando lo conocí en su casa de Bogotá - porqué quería escribir sobre mí. La verdad que no tenía ni idea porqué alguien como Gabo quería escribir sobre mí ya que nunca me creí tan interesante… 
En realidad quien quedó cautivada en ese encuentro fui yo y sí, quedé cautivada por su sentido del humor, por su calidez, por su humanidad y por su forma de hablar adornada de tantos aires costumbristas que solo a él le pertenecían. 
Realmente conversar con Gabo era cómo entrar en otra dimensión ajena al resto de los mortales. Era ver a un hombre entrado en años explorar el mundo de los otros como si fuese un niño, con una curiosidad inagotable, con una sed de saber y de inventar también… Me acuerdo cuando me decía “Shakira, si no me lo cuentas, me lo invento”… Así que para mí fue un honor cuando me pidió escribir para la película que trataba de abarcar “El Amor En Los Tiempos Del Cólera” y sí, escribí dos de mis mejores canciones hasta la fecha que fueron “Hay Amores” y “Despedida”… Como podía negarme a semejante honor y lujo de poder participar en un proyecto en el que estuviera involucrado Gabriel García Márquez? 
Él lo dijo una vez: “Recordar es fácil para aquellos que tienen buena memoria y olvidar es difícil para los que tienen corazón”. Que sepas Gabo que mantenemos en nuestros corazones todo lo que dejaste en ellos y te seguimos recordando para mantenerte vivo.
Shak

I’m writing this post about the upcoming midterm elections on November 6th, in which I’ll be voting in the state of Tennessee. In the past I’ve been reluctant to publicly voice my political opinions, but due to several events in my life and in the world in the past two years, I feel very differently about that now.  I always have and always will cast my vote based on which candidate will protect and fight for the human rights I believe we all deserve in this country. I believe in the fight for LGBTQ rights, and that any form of discrimination based on sexual orientation or gender is WRONG. I believe that the systemic racism we still see in this country towards people of color is terrifying, sickening and prevalent. 
I cannot vote for someone who will not be willing to fight for dignity for ALL Americans, no matter their skin color, gender or who they love.  Running for Senate in the state of Tennessee is a woman named Marsha Blackburn. As much as I have in the past and would like to continue voting for women in office, I cannot support Marsha Blackburn. Her voting record in Congress appalls and terrifies me. She voted against equal pay for women. She voted against the Reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act, which attempts to protect women from domestic violence, stalking, and date rape. She believes businesses have a right to refuse service to gay couples. She also believes they should not have the right to marry. These are not MY Tennessee values. I will be voting for Phil Bredesen for Senate and Jim Cooper for House of Representatives.  Please, please educate yourself on the candidates running in your state and vote based on who most closely represents your values. For a lot of us, we may never find a candidate or party with whom we agree 100% on every issue, but we have to vote anyway.
So many intelligent, thoughtful, self-possessed people have turned 18 in the past two years and now have the right and privilege to make their vote count. I recently returned from a solo trip to #Egypt and have SO much to say about it (I’ll do my best to break it up over the next few days lol)! I’ll be honest, I’d been holding off on traveling to Egypt for YEARS. A big part of that had to do with the stories I’d heard of women having negative experiences there. There’s no wrong or right way to travel—that’s for sure. And one person’s experience doesn’t automatically mean that it’s going to be the same for someone else. Good or bad. I appreciate honest accounts of travel experiences, because it helps me understand when I really need to do my research and decide if it’s the right destination for me or not. Some destinations I feel totally comfortable traveling to on a whim without doing an ounce of research. But, even with so much confidence in myself traveling on my own, there are still some places I research tirelessly, and make plans to ensure my safety. This was one of those places. I’m so happy that I had such a positive experience, met so many insanely friendly locals (a total stranger literally handed me their baby), and got to live out my lifelong dream of seeing the creations of Ancient Egyptians with my own two eyes.

Our amazing Earth ????
••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••••
For seven years, I’ve been sharing on this platform, encouraging others to get out and see the world. However, this #EarthDay, I am struggling to limit my message to “let’s take better care of our planet” when I’m well aware of the contradiction that is my life. Sure, I “refuse the straw,” haven’t eaten meat in over 10 years, carry a re-usable water bottle and shopping bags, and try to live as green as I can. But, how can I sit here and encourage people to explore our world when the issue of air travel is that, on an individual level, it accounts for more carbon emissions than any other human activity? I have to take accountability for my actions and the real issues of an “extreme” travel lifestyle. I have flown nearly 1,000,000 air miles in my lifetime. I can’t even do the math on the impact that has had on our environment. A few years ago, I was flying nearly every week for a YEAR. Instagram is an easy place to glamorize this lifestyle and I would be a hypocrite in not admitting that I’ve played a big role in contributing to it. Posting pretty pictures of exotic destinations and saying how much I love our planet is one thing. But then opting to jump on 10 flights a month is a very different reality. Actionable change to reduce your emissions by traveling smarter is the only way to truly decrease your carbon footprint as a traveler. While I can’t promise that I’ll never take another flight, I feel that accountability is the first step in becoming a more conscious traveler. Last year, I proactively cut my flying from the previous year in half, and I am committed to continuing to fly less and more consciously for years to come. I put together a blog post on how I'm flying less this year, and how I'm pledging to offset my carbon footprint for EVERY flight I take. This isn’t for praise, but rather, to share the knowledge I’ve acquired through countless hours of research so that we can all become better travelers, and to help support causes that make a difference like reforestation and ocean conservation.

This was the last morning of a week-long road trip along the Garden Route of South Africa. I was taking my parents across the country, showing them some of the highlights of this beautiful place I’ve been calling home for over 2 years.
?My dad had been dreaming of visiting Jeffrey’s Bay since he was a kid. He grew up in Southern California, part of the “Endless Summer” generation forever chasing the perfect wave. Our road trip soundtrack of classic rock — Led Zeppelin, Pink Floyd and the Rolling Stones — played on repeat as we drove through landscapes of mountain passes, massive canyons, epic coastlines, and finally ending in J Bay.

It’s an amazing feeling to give your parents some of their “firsts.” I think that’s one of the craziest parts of adulthood — realizing that you can eventually teach your parents things.

In case you missed it, my dad had to get his passport for this trip and this was his first time out of the US in 50 years. It took me TEN YEARS to finally get him on a plane.

The trip was amazing, but not without some serious hiccups. On day 2 of our road trip, while we were cycling around the beautiful Knysna lagoon, my mom fell and broke her collarbone.

Despite months of planning so that their trip would be perfect, it felt like everything was falling apart. I was dreading for my dad to say something along the lines of “I knew we shouldn’t have come.” But, those words never came. Low and behold, we finished our entire road trip, my mom bandaged up like a bird fallen from the nest. (The good news is she was out of pain in a few days and she’s having her surgery here with one of the best surgeons in South Africa.) We reached the southernmost tip of Africa, felt the chill of the Indian Ocean, tried new foods, and drove on the left side of the road. And, we watched the sun rise in the east and the sun set in the west in the same day.??This may seem like just another pretty beach sunrise photo on IG. But, on this morning, my dad said to me, “I finally understand why you travel.” And perhaps that’s why it’s one of the most significant photos I’ve ever posted. x

Two years ago today, someone that was a big part of my early travels ended her life.

I’ve never really opened up about it even though I have thought about her nearly every day since I got the news.

I carry a burden that evolves from anger, to guilt, to sorrow. It pops up when I don’t always expect it, but especially around the holidays and when I write or talk about destinations we traveled together.

One of the proudest things in my life is working together with her to raise over $5,500 for an orphanage in Peru. We traveled to Cusco to spend Christmas Day with the girls, then spent 4 days trekking the Inca Trail.

From the outside in, she had achieved so much in just 28 years. Working beside corporate bigwigs, traveling the world, and supporting charitable causes. When she passed, it came as a huge shock to everyone around her.

While I may never know her “why?” something I’ve learned is that, often times, the happiest people carry the most demons— and that’s what makes social media hard to swallow sometimes.

Despite what you see in media and online, life isn’t easy 100% of the time for ANYONE. You can’t assume that anything online is the ultimate truth. IG is the highlight reel of our lives.

So, if anyone on IG ever makes you feel less of yourself, PLEASE unfollow them, or at the very least, mute them. This platform should be uplifting and inspiring—so choose who you let in carefully.

If you find yourself putting on a happy face to stay strong for those around you, it’s important to give yourself a break. It’s ok to be vulnerable. Open up to someone about your pain— you are not a burden for asking for help.

So many of our challenges and disappointments in life are completely out of our control. There will always be hard times but there will also always be hope— we just have to choose to see it and pursue it relentlessly. Especially when it’s hardest to see.

As a travel blogger, I feel an obligation to demystify my lifestyle. You won’t resolve your insecurities by painting a picture of a perfect life. Happiness also isn’t found in faraway destinations. It’s got to be nourished and harvested within ourselves first—  the rest is just icing on the cake :)

“We didn’t realize we were making memories. We just knew we were having fun.” - Winnie the Pooh ??

It helps me tap into the realm of “anything is possible.” We all know the expression “don’t grow up,” which is I think a bit unrealistic.
